<HEADLINE> U.S. Business Leader Calls for Permanent MFN to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A top business representative of
the United States pledged here Tuesday to resist a "growing
isolationism" in the U.S. Congress while urging greater market
access for U.S. products and services in China and throughout
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Donohue, president and chief executive officer of the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, who is on a three-day visit to Hong Kong
for talks with government and business leaders, made the comments
during a luncheon speech organized by the American Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong (AmCham).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce is a powerful Washington-based
business lobby representing 3 million companies and organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The American business community is waging a strong battle
against those who would shut the United States off from world
markets," Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
"We oppose unilateral sanctions and support permanent
most-favored nation trading status for China. We want to see China
assume membership in the World Trade Organization under
commercially viable terms."
</P>
<P>
The chamber chief forecast that MFN for China "will, after the
normal noisy debate, be renewed again this year" -- setting the
stage for a push to make it permanent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Donohue emphasized, Asian economies,
including China, "must move more swiftly to open markets, increase
access to American products and services and reform economic
institutions."
</P>
<P>
"That's the key to economic revival in the region and it is
essential for maintaining positive and constructive relations with
the United States," he added.
</P>
<P>
In addition to his AmCham speech, Donohue will meet with Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region and other government officials and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I want to convey the message that American business greatly
values its relationship with a strong and viable Hong Kong. The
SAR is our 12th largest export market with two-way trade reaching
25 billion U.S. dollars annually. Our country has 16 billion U.S.
dollars invested here and nearly 50,000 Americans live here. Hong
Kong is our gateway to southern China and Southeast Asia," Donohue
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. chamber president also said his organization is
leading the effort in Washington, D.C., to provide 18 billion U.S.
dollars in funds to the International Monetary Fund to help
stabilize Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Despite current economic problems, Donohue expressed confidence
in Hong Kong's economic future. "Hong Kong will reign as a global
business capital in the 21st century because the fundamentals here
are so strong," Donohue concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
