<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moscow Wants More Say in Russia-NATO Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia wants to have more say in
its relations with the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO),
a senior defense official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
General Leonid Ivashov, head of the Defense Ministry's main
directorate for international cooperation, told reporters that
Moscow is against NATO attempts to discuss only general issues with
it.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to speak about the character and scope of
military exercises, on training NATO armed forces, on the system
of their combat readiness, to learn about the modernization of the
NATO infrastructure," the Interfax news agency quoted Ivashov as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is prepared to disclose its plans related to all the
above issues, including on its defense policy and military
doctrine, on an equal basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Russian defense minister Igor Sergeyev
complained to Henry Shelton, chairman of U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, that he was misled over NATO's air exercises over Albania
and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The war games were seen as a show of force by NATO to pressure
Yugoslav President Solobodan Milosevic on its Kosovo region, where
ethnic Albanians are demanding independence.
</P>
<P>
Moscow recalled its military envoy to NATO following the
exercises. The Interfax news agency, quoting a source with the
Defense Ministry, said it was a protest against the maneuvers,
although Moscow gave no official reason for the recall.
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO signed a Founding Act last year.
</P>
<P>
Ivashov said mutual suspicion has considerably decreased since
the signing of the document and the establishment of a Joint
Permanent Council.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO at first wanted to turn the council into a
decorative body that would allow NATO to avoid discussing with
Russia any serious issues of European security while demonstrating
"wonderful relations" between NATO and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The general listed three goals in Russia's cooperation with
NATO.
</P>
<P>
The first is to work together with NATO in changing the
approaches to building the European security system by giving top
priority to political measures and legal obligations rather than
the use of force.
</P>
<P>
The second goal, Ivashov said, is to prevent those nostalgic
for the "Cold War" from "taking us back to those times".
</P>
<P>
"Such forces do exist, and they are more numerous in NATO than
in Russia," he added.
</P>
<P>
The third goal is to use its cooperation with NATO to ensure
the security of Russia and other European countries, including
nations other than NATO members.
</P>
<P>
"If Russia is allowed to participate in NATO's activities, this
participation should be serious, constructive and fair," Ivashov
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
