<HEADLINE> E. Coli Sickens 4,000 in Illinois </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 4,000 people fell ill
in Illinois after eating potato salad in which a form of the E.
coli bacterium was found, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
Health officials said that a virulent form of E. coli also
sickened at least six children in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The Illinois case was the largest documented outbreak in the
United States of the strain called enterotoxigenic Escherichia
coli, or ETEC, Cook County Health Department officials were quoted
as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bacterium was identified in stool samples from three
victims of the illness known as "traveler's diarrhea," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The group of people became ill after eating potato salad
prepared by Iwan's Deli and Catering for several hundred parties
in the Chicago area over the weekend of June 6.
</P>
<P>
Health officials in Georgia were searching for the source or
sources of a more dangerous strain of E. coli that has sickened
six children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
