<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi University Looking at New Ways to Raise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The University of Malawi is
looking at unusual ways ranging from embarking on industrial
production to privatizing some of its services in a bid to raise
money after the government cut its funding to the institution.
</P>
<P>
Zambia News Agency Tuesday quoted Professor Brown Chimphamba,
vice-chancellor of the university, as saying in an interview in
Blantyre Monday that the time has come for the state-funded
university to follow in the footsteps of foreign universities
which fund themselves through minor industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor College, a constituent college of the university,
will set up a starch processing firm with the aim of generating
revenue for the cash-strapped institution, he sai.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the College of Medicine has embarked on
embalming bodies at a fee to raise money for its laboratory and
for the purchase of teaching facilities.
</P>
<P>
Other income-generating projects on the cards for colleges of
medicine and nursing are the running of paying wards and private
clinics.
</P>
<P>
Instead of letting the university campus lie idle during
holidays, its various facilities will be allowed to be hired for
local as well as international conferences, said Chimphamba.
</P>
<P>
It is also being negotiated within the rank and file of the
university that some course programs be run by correspondence
from diploma to degree level, especially those courses that do
not need laboratory work such as law and humanities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the university will start admitting students from
the Southern African Development Community (SADC) region,
especially in the College of Medicine, who will be paying their
fees in foreign currency, said the vice-chancellor.
</P>
<P>
The university also considers to privatize some of its
departments to reduce funds it spends on these departments,
especially the catering and maintenance departments.
</P>
<P>
Other fiscal measures recommended to the university by the
Malawi Institute of Management, the consulting firm that is hired
to find ways to bail the country out of its financial crisis, is
the introduction of scholarships.
</P>
<P>
Students who do not get scholarships will be required to get
loans from banks and other financial institutions, while others
will have to get their fees from their parents or guardians,
according to Chimphamba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
