<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Promote Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Five southern African
countries will spend about 90 million U.S. Dollars on joint
development projects in the sub-region, Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Business people from Botswana, Lesotho, Mozambique, Swaziland
and Zimbabwe have signed 40 letters of intent for more than 89
million Dollars during a regional forum on investment, recently
held in Maputo, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
SABA quoted Mozambican Minister of Industry, Trade and Tourism
Oldemiro Baloi as saying that southern Africa was "an important
and large market".
</P>
<P>
About 75 businessmen from the five countries presented 112
investment projects, largely covering agriculture, mining,
textiles and tourism, the forum organizers said. 
</P>
