<HEADLINE> India Publishes Vajpayee's Letter to Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming Colombo summit
of the South Asian countries would enable India and Pakistan to
decide on how to proceed further with the stalled bilateral
dialogue, said Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said in a letter to his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz
Sharif, on June 14 that the presence of the two prime ministers in
Colombo next month would allow them to hold bilateral dialogue on
all issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister said New Delhi is committed to
fostering peaceful and friendly relations with Islamabad and wants
to develop a stable structure of cooperation between the two
neighbors, according to the letter made public here Tuesday by a
spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Prime ministers of the two countries are scheduled to meet at
the Colombo summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) which is scheduled to open on July 29.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Vajpayee urged Pakistan to engage in dialogue with
India to resolve all outstanding issues in accordance with the
Simla Agreement reached between the two countries in 1972.
</P>
</TEXT>
