<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Macedonia Oppose Military Intervention on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece and the Republic of
Macedonia, a former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM), have
agreed on peaceful means rather than military option to resolve
the crisis raging through the Serbian southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos said after talks with
his FYROM counterpart Blagoj Handziski that they had lots to gain
with a peaceful resolution and much to lose with military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Handziski, who is on a two-day trip in Greece
starting on Monday, said the two nations shared the same view on
the crisis of Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians seek independence
from Belgrade and integration into Albania.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has stripped the autonomy in early 1990s from ethnic
Albanians who make up 90 percent of the Kosovo population and has
built up military presence for crackdown on break-away Albanians
in the province.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people, most of whom women, children and the
elderly, have died this year in fighting between Serb forces and
ethnic Albanians since the tensions escalated in February.
</P>
<P>
The tour of Handziski is the first by such a high-ranking
representative of the FYROM and follows a visit to Skopje by
Pangalos last year.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have improved in recent
years, but both sides remain divided over a final name for the
FYROM.
</P>
<P>
Greece believes any use of the name "Macedonia" implies claims
on the northern Greek province of Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said both sides have agreed on keeping the examination
of the name issue within the framework of the United Nations,
while Handziski said efforts were made to achieve a desired result
through reciprocal compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Launches Plan for Humanitarian Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland formally launched
Tuesday its plan for a humanitarian fund to combat poverty,
violence and human rights abuses but the plan would have to await
Swiss voters' consent.
</P>
<P>
The planned Solidarity Foundation will be open for public
comment until mid-September with a view to submitting draft
legislation to parliament before the end of the year, the Swiss
Finance Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss will vote in a referendum to decide on amending the
constitution and abolishing Switzerland's gold backing for the
Swiss franc. This would provide around 4.7 billion U.S. dollars of
gold for the fund and some 6.7 billion U.S. dollars for other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
After the plan to halve gold reserves was approved on May 27 by
the cabinet, Swiss Finance Minister Kaspar Villiger told reporters
that he hoped the parliament would pass the plan by the end of
this year and that a referendum could follow in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
Villiger said that Switzerland could not start selling half of
its gold reserves before late 1999 or early 2000.
</P>
<P>
To avoid disrupting prices on world gold markets, Villiger
said, the selling of roughly half of Switzerland's gold reserves
would probably be spread over five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to set up the Solidarity Foundation was announced
in March 1997 by the then Swiss president Arnold Koller. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
