<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Seals Deals with Zambia in Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) signed here Tuesday two agreements with the Zambian
government totalling about 25 million U.S. Dollars in food aid to
support the country's nutrition and food-for-work activities.
</P>
<P>
At a signing ceremony held at the Ministry of Finance, WFP
representative Techeste Zergaber said the assistance is part of
the five-year commitment of 31.9 million Dollars under the new
country program approved last October by the WFP executive board,
according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
He said 47,723 tons of food aid and essential non-food items
will be provided under the agreement for the implementation of
the supplementary feeding and urban food-for-work activities.
</P>
<P>
The supplement will boost the nutrition status of
malnourished children, expectant and breast-feeding mothers,
orphans and the chronically ill, and patients suffering from
tuberculosis (TB).
</P>
<P>
Zergaber said 30,136 tons of maize meal, sugar, pulse, dried
skim milk and high energy protein supplement is targeted for
228,000 malnourished under-five children, 60,000 pregnant and
lactating women and over 52,000 orphans.
</P>
<P>
Under Zambia's urban food-for-food work program, more than
17,500 tons of maize meal, vegetable oil, pulse and salt will be
distributed to 45,000 food insecure low-income residents in the
unplanned urban settlements.
</P>
<P>
David Diangamo, acting permanent secretary of Ministry of
Finance who signed on behalf of the Zambian government, praised
WFP for the initiative and commitment in the funding of the two
programs which are ready for implementation.
</P>
<P>
He described the assistance as "timely", adding that it will
help improve the social conditions as well as raise the standard
of living of the Zambian people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
