<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Ends Ban on Air Ticket Sale to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Tuesday lifted
a decade-old ban on its airline companies' selling tickets for
trips from the U.S. to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This decision came despite a car bomb blast and a grenades
explosion went off here in the capital in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
The lifting of the ban was announced by its embassy in Beirut
in a statement, which says the U.S. allows its airlines to sell
tickets for trips to Lebanon and transport baggages for its
citizens and foreigners to Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. imposed the ban on its airlines after a suicide truck
bombing in 1983 killed 241 U.S. servicemen and separate attacks on
U.S. embassy and citizens in 1984 in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. has removed the ban on its citizens
travelling here last year and the ban concerning airlines, it
still refuses to reopen direct flights to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of States Madeleine Albright has warned that
Lebanon is still a dangerous place to visit.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, three rocket-propelled grenades exploded only 500
meters away from the U.S. Embassy in the eastern part of Beirut,
causing no damage to people and the compound.
</P>
<P>
Three days earlier, a booby-trapped car exploded in the
capital's commercial area, claiming two persons' lives.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese politicians said these incidents, which are under
investigations, were intended to hurt the stability of Lebanon
which is recovering from the devastating 1975-1990 civil war.
</P>
</TEXT>
