<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Grain Prices at Levels 5 Years Ago: IGC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- As a result of two successive large
world harvests, grain prices were back almost to their low levels
five years ago, the International Grains Council (IGC) announced
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the volume of trade in 1998/99 would probably show
little change, world demand was continuing to expand, but at a
slower pace particularly in Pacific Asia, the IGC said.
</P>
<P>
Assisted by the recent moderate rebuilding of stocks, the
council estimated an approximate balance between total grain
supply and demand in 1998/99 would be achieved.
</P>
<P>
At its latest semi-annual session, the council said the members
exchanged views on the possible grains trade implications of the
Biosafety Protocol being negotiated under U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the council requested the Secretariat to begin
to monitor government decisions in both exporting and importing
countries concerning approvals of genetically modified cereals in
production and trade.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Argentina, the council decided that it
will hold a Special Grains Conference on 2 December 1998 in Buenos
Aires on the theme "Facing the new century challenges for grain
markets."
</P>
<P>
Participants will focus on the next WTO negotiations, the
development and enlargement of regional trading arrangements, and
the prevailing market perspectives for different sectors of the
world grains economy, the IGC added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
