<HEADLINE> Pay Talks between Zimbabwean Govt, CSEA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations between the
Zimbabwean government and the Civil Service Employees Association
(CSEA) over increases in the cost of living adjustment and other
allowances have come to a deadlock, CSEA officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The association's assistant executive secretary Christopher
Gwatidzo said representatives of the government and the
association met last week but could not reach an agreement as
there was a big gap between the government's offer and the civil
servants' demands.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was adjourned after civil servants representatives
requested to consult with the workers, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Gwatidzo said the civil servants are demanding a 30 percent
cost of living adjustment. But the government is offering
between nine and ten percent.
</P>
<P>
The government is also proposing to increase transport and
housing allowances by 30 and 40 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
CSEA President Kudakwashe Sinyoro said his association will
hold a meeting with the government representatives on Wednesday
and, if no agreement is reached, civil servants will go on strike
any time from next Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
