<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAC Reviews Food Aid Policy Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- For the year ending 30 June 1998,
shipment under the Food Aid Convention were estimated to total
over 5.4m. tons compared with 5.7m. in the previous year, the Food
Aid Committee announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The shipments therefore remained slightly abover members'
combined minimum obligation of 5.35m. tons, the committee said in
its statement released here.
</P>
<P>
The committee noted that, because of increases in other forms
of assistance to countries in Asia, Australia was obliged to
reduce its minimum annual commitment from 300,000 tons to 250,000
tons with effect from 1 July 1998.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that cereals production in many countries was
likely to remain above trend in 1998. However, several countries
were facing food emergencies, largely because of EI Nino related
floods or droughts.
</P>
<P>
The Food Aid Committee said that lower international wheat
prices were reducing the food import bills of many developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, import costs for a number of least developed countries
had increased because of their larger requirements.
</P>
<P>
The committee expressed great concern at the worsening food
situation in some countries in Far East Asia, especially
Indonesia, where food prices were escalating beyond the reach of
many of the poorest people.
</P>
<P>
The committee confirmed its intention to bring a new Food Aid
Convention into effect on 1 July 1999. To this end, it will aim to
complete the substantive negotiations by the time of its next
session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
