<HEADLINE> Italian Delegation in Somalia in Peace Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A three-member high level
delegation from the government of Italy is now in the Somali
capital Mogadishu for a reported new assessment regarding
Somalia's peace process.
</P>
<P>
The delegation led by General Luka Rabiola, arrived here late
Monday afternoon and was escorted by heavily armed militiamen to
the part of the city controlled by faction leader Ali Mahdi
Mohamed.
</P>
<P>
According to the top officers of Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Rabiola
and his delegation has met Ali Mahdi Mohamed and senior officials
from his faction at his residence Monday night and discussed
about several issues concerning the political and socio-economic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The scope of the visit by the delegation is said to be related
to a new assessment by Italy regarding Somalia's peace process
and the political settlement in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The sources also said the delegation is trying to find
possible ways in which Italy could help in the re-establishment
of Mogadishu's public services including the health, water,
electricity and road communications sectors.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to Ali Mahdi's office also said the delegation,
which will also meet other faction leaders in the capital, is
aimed at consolidating an earlier agreed tentative in which a
strong police force will be established for Mogadishu with the
help of the Italian government.
</P>
<P>
Italy has agreed upon the maintenance of a 5,000-strong police
force for the capital and its surrounding areas at this
particular moment when Ali Mahdi Mohamed and Hussein Mohamed
Aidid could be characterized as very close allies for the first
time since the civil war broke out in Somalia, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi's officials have characterized the meeting as
cordial and fruitful.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, in collaboration with some Somalis, is also
trying to normalize a strained relation between some of north
Mogadishu subclans and Italy following the arrest of a Somali
man, Hashi Omar, in Rome on January 12 this year for allegedly
involving in the killing of an Italian journalist, Elaria Alpi
and her camera man, in Mogadishu in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Giuseppe Cassini, Italy's former special envoy to Somalia,
took Hashi Omar from Mogadishu together with a group of Somalis
as testimonies for the Italian troops' human rights violations
during their stay in Somalia as part of the UNOSOM forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the north Mogadishu politicians have
managed to calm down the relatives of Hashi Omar before the
Italian delegation arrived Monday.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest level Italian delegation that visits
Mogadishu since the visit of the Italian Under Secretary of State
Rino Serri on July 29 last year, when the diplomacy of Italy has
failed to bring together Mogadishu's faction leaders on a common
luncheon sponsored by Cassini. 
</P>
</TEXT>
