<HEADLINE> Arab League to Discuss Jerusalem Expansion Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) will hold a
meeting Thursday to discuss the impacts of an Israeli plan to
expand the authority of Jerusalem, the Middle East News Agency
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, at the level of permanent delegates to AL and to
be held at Palestinians' request, will come up with measures to
deal with the critical situation in the Mideast peace process,
Palestinian delegate Mohamed Sobeih told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said that he reported the preliminary information on
Israel's plan during a meeting of permanent delegates, and handed
a note to AL chief Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid on Monday, outlining
the Israeli expansion scheme of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet Sunday approved the expansion plan, which
will set up an "umbrella authority" for the Jerusalem municipality
over eight West Bank Jewish settlements to the north, east and
south of the city.
</P>
<P>
Under agreement signed between the Palestinians and Israel, the
issue of Jerusalem will be negotiated in the final status talks
and neither side should take unilateral actions to change the
status of the city.
</P>
<P>
Should the expansion plan be implemented, Israel will increase
the area of Jerusalem to 600 square kilometers from 108 square
kilometers, the Palestinian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is paving roads leading up to Jerusalem
which incurs forfeiture of more Palestinian property and lands and
the isolation of Arab suburbs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured the traditionally Arab East Jerusalem in the
1967 Middle East War. Relevant United Nations Security Council
resolutions stipulate that East Jerusalem is part of the occupied
Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of their
future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia to Increase Fishing Quotas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Namibia said Tuesday it
would increase fishing quotas because stocks along the country's
coast have recovered.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by the Chamber of Commerce and
Industry in the port-city of Walvis Bay, 389 kilometers west of
the capital, Windhoek, the Southern African Broadcasting
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Hrywniak, president of the chamber, said a report by
fisheries experts has confirmed the revival of depleted marine
resource.
</P>
<P>
Hywniak said the renewal of the industry will make up losses
suffered during poor fishing seasons in the recent years.
</P>
<P>
The city of Walvis Bay, whose port is the deepest in southern
Africa, is 70 percent dependent on fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
Catches of different fish species was cut last year due to bad
weather condition, which drastically reduced Namibia's fish
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Fishing is one of Namibia's key economic sectors, accounting
for at least 11 percent of total export earnings per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
