<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests against Turkish Nuclear Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot parliament has
protested against Turkey's plan to build two nuclear reactors on
its southern coast, near the divided Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
In a letter released to the press Tuesday, President of the
Cypriot House of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou told his
counterparts of Mediterranean and European Union countries that
Turkey's plan is "causing a lot of uneasiness and anxiety to the
people of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reportedly decided to construct two nuclear reactors
this year in the earthquake-prone area of Akkuyu on its southern
coast, about 185 kilometers north of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot people have "legitimate concerns about the impacts
on life, health and environment emanating from such reactors,"
Kyprianou said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Cyprus' strong objection to the materialization of
the Turkish plan and demanded that all possible measures be taken
so that Turkey refrain from going ahead with its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
He quoted results of independent studies as saying that the
proposed venue of the reactors is close to the Akkuyu fault, an
active seismic zone, which makes the selection of this particular
area an extremely dangerous and risky option.
</P>
<P>
He said the proximity of Cyprus to Akkuyu, its small size, and
prevailing wind patterns and sea currents "are serious parameters
that will exacerbate the magnitude of the impact" in case of an
earthquake, malfunction, poor operation or even under normal
operating conditions.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
troops and took over the northern third in the wake of a failed
coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
