<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brent Crude Futures Celebrate 10 Years of Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Petroleum
Exchange's (IPE) biggest contract, Brent Crude futures, celebrates
its 10th birthday here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Brent futures form part of the Brent Blend complex, which acts
as the pricing benchmark for two thirds of the world's
internationally traded crude oil supplies in the Middle East,
Europe, North and South America, Africa and the Far East.
</P>
<P>
The IPE said Brent is among the top three most actively traded
energy futures contracts in the world. The success of the contract
has helped the IPE to evolve into a truly global institution of
offering risk management facilities to companies all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
This year has been the most successful yet for the contract. So
far this year volumes traded have reached 6,622,927 lots (more
than 6.6 billion barrels). This represents a 40 percent increase
on the same period for last year.
</P>
<P>
On average Brent futures have traded almost 57,000 lots a day
in 1998 (57 million barrels a day). This is equivalent to about 75
percent of daily world oil consumption.
</P>
<P>
Lynton Jones, chief executive of the IPE, said, "The rapid
expansion of the IPE's business over the last 10 years has been
largely due to the success of Brent Crude." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
