<HEADLINE> WFP Expands Operations to Supply Food to Hungry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
said Tuesday that it has decided to establish and expand
alternate transport and logistics arrangements to ensure the
delivery of urgently needed humanitarian food aid to
approximately 4.3 million vulnerable people in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
A news release issued here by Justin Bagirishya, WFP country
director in Ethiopia, said the measures are taken in response to
the ongoing conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea which diverts
from Eritrean ports of Massawa and Assab to the port of Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
According to the news release, WFP negotiated this week with
Ethiopian officials, Djibouti seaport representatives and
transport companies to ensure that over the coming months 240,000
metric tons of much-needed food aid will be regularly processed
through the port of Djibouti and safely delivered by rail cars
and trucks.
</P>
<P>
WFP is also in the process of hiring some 200 commercial
trucks to ensure that once food aid is released from the port, it
can be quickly delivered to the needy, the release added.
</P>
<P>
The 240,000 tons of food aid were contributed to Ethiopia by
WFP, the European Union and others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
