<HEADLINE> British Paper Stands by S. African-Libyan Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- London's Sunday Telegraph
newspaper stuck to its weekend report of a secret
500-million-U.S. dollar arms-for-oil deal between South Africa
and Libya, despite denials by the South African government, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Con Coughlin, the newspaper's foreign editor who wrote the
story, said he "stood behind the story 100 percent," SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Coughlin said in a statement faxed to SAPA that he was
surprised at the vehemence of the South African government's
denial, given that the deal had been negotiated when South
African President Nelson Mandela visited Libya last year.
</P>
<P>
Attempts to check the story with South African authorities
proved futile "because of their desire to keep details of the
arrangement secret," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly I cannot reveal my sources on such a sensitive
subject. To do so would be to place them in peril."
</P>
<P>
Mandela's office said in a statement Monday that the paper
should at least try to verify its information with
representatives of the South African government.
</P>
<P>
"What is utterly disgusting about this article is that it is a
pure fabrication invented by the newspaper and its unnamed
sources," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Coughlin denied the South African government's claim that the
purpose of the story was to sabotage the country's democracy.
</P>
<P>
"I covered the 1994 elections for the Sunday Telegraph and
greatly admired the manner in which Present Nelson Mandela
conducted himself during the campaign."
</P>
<P>
Coughlin reported on Sunday that Mandela had approved a deal
to supply Libya with weapons and military spare parts in return
for cut-price oil in violation of United Nations sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The statement of the South African side said neither Mandela
nor the government and its agencies had entered into any talks --
let alone concluded any deals -- with Libya on arms for oil.
</P>
<P>
If such a decision was ever taken, the government would
publicly declare its intentions and fully state its reasons for
doing so, it said.
</P>
<P>
An arms embargo and flight ban were imposed on Libya after the
1988 Lockerbie air crash over Scotland, in which two Libyans were
suspected to have bombed the Pan Am aircraft.
</P>
<P>
South Africa maintains close relations with Libya, which was
accused by the West of sponsoring terrorism. Mandela visited
Libya twice in October last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
