<HEADLINE> Mubarak Says Arab Reconciliation on Bumpy Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said Tuesday that the Arab reconciliation process is still on a
bumpy road, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the ruling National Democratic Party members of the
newly-elected Shura Council, Mubarak noted that the Iraqi
invasion of Kuwait in 1990 torpedoed all efforts to effect Arab
reconciliation which was "within reach in that year."
</P>
<P>
"At the time, the Arab leaders were about to agree on meeting
for regular summits every November," he added.
</P>
<P>
"But now Arab reconciliation is facing some obstacles," the
Egyptian leader said.
</P>
<P>
Citing the differences which preceded the June 1996 pan-Arab
summit in Cairo, Mubarak said convening an Arab summit now is "not
so easy as it requires reconciling all orientations and interests."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president made the comments as the Arab countries
are holding consultations on the possibility of holding an Arab
summit to hammer out a unified position in the deadlocked Mideast
peace process. But differences have been reported on the venue,
timing and agenda of the summit proposed by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has been stagnated since Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu took office in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Turning to Arab economic cooperation, Mubarak said Egypt is
seeking to set up free trade zones with a number of Arab countries
with a view to facilitating the project of an Arab Common Market.
</P>
<P>
"However, no development is possible without stability, which
in turn would not be achieved without peace," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated his initiative to free the Middle East
from all weapons of mass destruction. In this connection, he
highlighted his proposal to convene an international conference
under the United Nations on phasing out nuclear weaponry from the
whole world between 15 and 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"The countries of the world are convinced that there is a
danger posed to humanity and this can not be controlled in view of
the arms race as happened in India and Pakistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that Egypt does not intend to possess nuclear arms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
