<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: New Opportunity for Developing Sino-U.S. Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- In a few days' time,
U.S. President Bill Clinton will be in China for nine days, making
himself the first U.S. head of state in Beijing in nine years.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, it will be President Clinton's first overseas tour
dedicated to a single nation ever since he assumed the White House
presidency more than five years ago. The travel arrangement alone
reflects the priority given by the Clinton administration to
pushing ahead U.S. relations with China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's visit to China is in return to Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's tour of the United States last October, during which
they agreed to initiate the process of building a constructive and
strategic Sino-U.S. partnership oriented toward the 21st century,
thus bringing the bilateral ties onto a new stage of growth.
</P>
<P>
Since President Jiang's U.S. tour, the momentum has been
building up for positively moving ahead the Sino-U.S. relations,
shown firstly in increased high-level exchanges of officials
nourishing their mutual understanding and coordination in
bilateral and international affairs; and secondly in expanded
channels for bilateral cooperation, including putting a 13-year
agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy into real practice
in March and subsequently allowing U.S. companies to compete on
the China market for supplying nuclear power facilities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, recent months have witnessed the two sides signing
agreements to establish a consultation mechanism for maritime
military safety and open up a presidential communications link
between Beijing and Washington, working more closely to fight
international drug trafficking rings, and exploring the avenues
for cooperation in areas such as environmental protection, energy
industry, and financial and insurance services.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, despite the Asian financial turmoil, economic
relations between China and the United States have been further
expanding, with their bilateral trade on the continued rise. And
confident about the sustainability of a healthy Chinese economy,
U.S. companies are enthusiastic about investing in China.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, both sides are taking positive steps to handle their
differences. On March 14, the Clinton administration announced
that it would no longer co-sponsor a resolution against China at
the United Nations conference on human rights in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Fifthly, on the issue of Taiwan, Clinton administration
officials have repeated, on different occasions, their commitment
not to support the concept of "two Chinas" or "one China, one
Taiwan," and not to back Taiwan's attempt for independence or
entry into the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Sixthly, the two countries have stepped up their consultation
and coordination on world affairs. One example was the June 4
meeting of foreign ministers from the five permanent member countries
of the U.N. Security Council in Geneva to curb a potential nuclear
arms race in South Asia. It was jointly proposed by China and the
United States, and chaired by China.
</P>
<P>
Noticeably, due to their different social systems, cultures and
historic backgrounds, China and the United States do hold
different views on certain issues. And the development of their
bilateral ties still has to face up to interference from some
forces within the United States. By submitting an anti-China
proposal prior to Clinton's visit to China, some lawmakers in
U.S. Congress were attempting to block and disrupt the improvement
of Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
However, the expansion of Sino-U.S. relations is the trend of
the time and the call of the two peoples. It is increasingly a
collective will of most Americans to maintain and better friendly
cooperation with China. On his part, President Clinton recently
told a group of U.S.-based Chinese journalists that he would
continue to stick up to his China policy of engagement and do his
best to defeat any legislation in Congress that would undermine
the ability of his administration to pursue the interests of the
United States and the interests of the American people in
developing a partnership with China and the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
From the "Ping-Pong diplomacy" in the early 1970s to the
commitment to a constructive and strategic partnership,
Sino-U.S. relations have not always been on a smooth development
path. While China is the world's largest developing country and
the United States the largest developed one, their relations are
crucial not only for the interests of the two countries and the
two peoples, but also for the peace and stability of Asia and the
world as a whole. With the end of the Cold War era and the shift
of the world towards multipolarization, interests shared by China
and the United States have not decreased, but rather increased. As
stated by Clinton in his meeting with Chinese journalists, current
cooperation between his country and China is more important than
any previous year's.
</P>
<P>
A recent public opinion poll in the United States suggests that
78 percent of Americans questioned favors Clinton's visit to
China, hoping that the two countries will further expand
cooperation. A number of American personages, including senior
officials in both present and former U.S. administrations, have
pointed out that Clinton's planned China tour is in line with the
interests of the United States. Noting that the two countries
share common interests in many ways, they have stressed that the
two sides should try their best to expand cooperation and reduce
divergences.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that President Clinton's visit to China would
help push forward the process initiated by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin for establishing between the two countries a constructive
and strategic partnership oriented toward the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
