<HEADLINE> UNDP Offers $120m Aid to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) Tuesday put forward a new package of cooperation
valuing 120 million U.S. Dollars to Mozambique for 1998-2001.
</P>
<P>
The new package is aimed at up-rooting poverty, improving the
management of environment, natural resources, economy and finance
and training personnel.
</P>
<P>
Frances Rodrigues, Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs and
Cooperation, and Emmanuel Casterle, UNDP representative to
Mozambique, attended the ceremony in which the program was
started.
</P>
<P>
Four agreements involving 16 million Dollars were also signed
concerning education, health, water suply and employment for the
first stage of the program.
</P>
<P>
Of the 120 million Dollars, 79 percent came from donor
nations, and the rest from a fund under the UNDP, according to
Mozambican News Agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Casterle said Mozambique is the first African country
receiving UNDP's out-of-budget aid.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP, which started offering aid to the southern African
country soon after it got independence in 1975, rendered it with
183 million Dollars during 1993-1997 period. 
</P>
