<HEADLINE> Tanzanians Urged to Get Used to Drinking Milk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma Tuesday called on citizens to get accustomed to
drinking milk which has not been habitual in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
"Drinking milk is good to your health," Juma said while
inaugurating the Dairy Week exhibitions at Mnazi Mmoja grounds in
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the speech, Juma inspected a procession of farmers,
dairymen and veterinarians who came from different parts of the
country to take part in the event, scheduled from June 23 to 27.
</P>
<P>
He also urged farmers to pay greater attention to quality than
quantity in cattle raising, saying too many large herds of cattle
are detrimental to the environment.
</P>
<P>
"Let us follow Botswana's style," he said. "The cattle are
kept in a few number but in high quality."
</P>
<P>
Juma suggested the application of modern techniques which he
said is the only solution to improving the quality in cattle
raising.
</P>
<P>
"Improve your quality so that the milk can meet the demand of
exports," he said to the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Vice-President said the government plans to
grant loans to local dairymen and urged them to form societies so
that they can be easier in getting loans.
</P>
<P>
Considering loans security, he said, it is difficult for the
government to grant loans to individuals who are not financially
strong.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Exhibitions Committee, Ngweshani Mbonde,
in his welcoming speech, prayed the government to exempt animal
husbandry from the Value Added Tax (VAT) as the industry is still
young.
</P>
<P>
Mbonde told reporters Monday that apart from the exhibitions,
participants will learn modern ways of farming and discuss how to
solve common problems.
</P>
<P>
This week's program includes distributing milk in different
dispensaries and hospitals in the city as a way of encouraging
milk drinking.
</P>
<P>
"It is shameful for a country like ours to have children
starving while we have so much milk only because milk drinking is
unaccustomed," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
