<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Assures Residents of Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
Tuesday assured the people of Fort Portal in the west and Uganda
in general of the government's determination to provide them with
security.
</P>
<P>
He made the assurance while visiting the Kichwamba Technical
College in western Kabarole district where over 80 students were
burnt to death and more than 100 others abducted by rebels of the
Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) on June 8, Radio Uganda reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said although there are some laxities in the army
which were held partly responsible for the massacre, the
government is trying to arm the army with better equipment
against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The president paid his deepest condolences to the families of
the dead and abducted as well as to all the people in Kichwamba,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to ADF rebels to lay down arms and surrender and
warned that this is the only way out for them. With the
modernization of the army, he said he believed the rebels will
have no chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, the president arrayed fears that rebels
have been gaining in strength, saying that some 300 rebels active
in the north have surrendered under the mounting pressure from
the government.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 ADF rebels staged a surprise pre-dawn attack at the
Kichwamba Technical College on June 8. Over 80 students in three
dormitories were killed in an inferno and more were abducted to
reinforce the rebels.
</P>
<P>
This relentless act of terror triggered fast fire from all
walks of life in Uganda and from the international community,
making the rebels' lonely base in the border area more isolated.
</P>
</TEXT>
