<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demirel: Turkey to Advance Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
said here Tuesday that Turkey attaches great importance to the
advancement of the Middle East peace process, which has been
deadlocked for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with visiting Palestinian Minister of
Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi, Demirel said in a written
statement that Turkey will continue to make contributions to the
peace process in the Middle East and to the peace and prosperity
of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
On her part, Ashrawi, who arrived here on Monday for a two-day
visit, said that she had informed Demirel of the latest
developments in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi said she believed that Turkey will make contributions
to pushing forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat will pay an official visit
to Turkey soon, she added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement issued by the Turkish Foreign Ministry
Tuesday said that "the Israeli decision to expand Jerusalem will
not contribute to stability and peace in the Middle East, although
it is said that the plan is based on just reasons."
</P>
<P>
It stressed that Turkey is opposed to unilateral modifications
in the status of Jerusalem, which is the core issue of the peace
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is concerned with the present state of the Middle East
peace process. Turkey demands that the obstacles in the way of the
peace process be lifted and the Oslo Agreement be obeyed," said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been deadlocked since March
last year over Israel's settlement building in East Jerusalem and
long-delayed withdrawal from the West Bank. Israel has rejected
a U.S. proposal on further redeployment, which was accepted by
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Turkey enjoyed close relations with
Israel. The military cooperation between the two countries has
sparked anger among Arab countries, particularly Syria who
believes it is the target of Turkish-Israeli military ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
