<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The New York Philharmonic
presented the finale of its '98 Asian Tour this evening at the
Great Hall of the People, winning resounding applause from an
appreciative audience including Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
Zhu met with Guenther, board chairman of the orchestra, and
Conductor Kurt Masur and other major performers prior to the
performance.
</P>
<P>
Zhu extended a warm welcome to the musicians on behalf of the
Chinese government and hailing their China tour as a significant
event in Sino-US cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Guenther said the orchestra will continue efforts to expand
ties between musical circles in the two nations and deepen mutual
understanding between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The New York Philharmonic, the oldest orchestra in the United
States with a history of 156 years, has toured to 352 cities in 52
countries on five continents. The most recent tour is the orchestra's
second in Asia and first in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton
wrote inscriptions praising the orchestra which presented two
concerts in Beijing on the eve of the latter's China tour.
</P>
<P>
The evening performance under the baton of Maestro Kurt Masur
included Beethoven's Leonore Overture No.3 and Symphony No.5, as
well as Barber's Violin Concerto. 
