<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Tighten Administrative Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to tighten controls
over the management of administrative charges and fines in a move
to rectify state financial order and improve administrative and
law enforecement departments.
</P>
<P>
A regulation issued today stipulates that items and criteria
for administrative charges must be strictly carried out in
accordance withe relevant directives issued the Central Committee
of the Communist Party of China and State Council. Departments are
prohibited from setting charge items and raising charges on their
own.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also calls for strengthening management over
notes, requiring public security departments, procurators, courts
and industrial and commercial administrative departments at all
levels to unifying notes issued by central and provincial
financial departments.
</P>
<P>
Decisions related to fines and payments of fines must be
separated. The regulation also stipulates that fines
should be remitted to institutions entrusted by financial
departments.
</P>
<P>
Administrative charges and fines must be deposited with
national treasury or in special capital account beyond the
financial budget, according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
The regulation stipulates that departments of finance, planning
and discipline inspection at all levels must introduce special
rectification programs related to existing charge items and
criteria with concerned departments. All rectified charge items
must be open to the general public for supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, EU Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australia and the European Union
(EU) Wednesday signed an agreement to boost their trade.
</P>
<P>
The Agreement on Mutual Recognition in Relation to Conformity
Assessment, Certificates and Markings (MRA) was signed by
Australian Industry, Science and Tourism Minister John Moore and
Vice President of the European Commission Leon Brittan.
</P>
<P>
Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim Fischer
and Foreign Minister Alexander Downer were present at the signing
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The agreement "will also slash costs by as much as 10 million
Australian dollars (6 million U.S. dollars) for Australian
exporters and up to 40 million Australian dollars (24 million U.S.
dollars) for European exporters," Moore and Brittan said in a
joint statement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows testing, inspection and certification of
products traded between Europe and Australia to be done in the
exporting country.
</P>
<P>
This is an alternative to carrying out checks at the
destination.
</P>
<P>
"Two-way trade covered by the agreement is currently 8 billion
Australian dollars (4.8 billion U.S. dollars annually) and today's
signing will lead to an opening up of markets which have
previously been rendered uneconomic by regulatory costs,"
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
The document covers simple pressure equipment, machinery, low
voltage electrical equipment and medical devices,
telecommunications terminal equipment, electromagnetic
compatibility and automotive products.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued Wednesday by the two parties said the
European Union has around 155 billion Australian dollars (93
billion U.S. dollars) worth of investment in Australia, which has
invested about 40 billion Australian dollars (24 billion U.S.
dollars) in total in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
During the signing ceremony, Brittan called on Australia and
the EU to deepen their relations, saying the EU market would be
the largest one in the world with a population of 370 million
after the introduction of a single European currency, the euro, on
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming introduction of the euro and current Asian
economic downturn "imply that it is in the interests of Europe and
Australia for us to deepen the relationship between us,
economically and politically," Brittan was quoted Wednesday by The
Australian, one of the leading newspapers in Australia, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It's shown Australia that you can't put all your eggs in the
Asian basket," he added.
</P>
<P>
To date, about 60 percent of Australia's annual export of goods
and services goes to Asian market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
