<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Slower Growth in Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The financial crises in Southeast
Asia has affected the implementation of China's budget over the
past five months, according to Finance Minister Xiang Huaicheng.
</P>
<P>
"The financial situation is packed with comparatively severe
possibilities," said Xiang in comments at the third meeting of
the Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC).
</P>
<P>
State revenues grew by 7.7 percent and expenditures by 12.8
percent during the January-May period when compared to last year's
same period, said Xiang.
</P>
<P>
He added that the severe financial situation has been the
result of lax taxation, insufficient domestic demand, sluggish
economic growth and the poor operations of state-owned businesses
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He said China will pour more funds into infrastructure,
education and science and technology in order to ensure
fulfillment of the eight percent economic growth target set by
central authorities.
</P>
<P>
Central authorities will also allocate special funds for grain
purchases, invest more into central and western regions of the
country and old industrial bases, support laid-off workers and
promoted the expansion of exports.
</P>
<P>
Xiang called for a crack down on violations of the taxation law
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
With regard to final accounting for revenues and expenditures
for 1997, Xiang said that 1997 revenues reached 483 billion yuan
(58 billion US dollars), up 13.3 percent on the previous
year. Expenditure hit 538.917 billion yuan, up 10.6 percent. The
nations also recorded a financial deficit of 55.8 billion yuan,
down 1.16 billion yuan when compared to the budgeted figure.
</P>
<P>
"The budget approved at the fifth meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress was implemented
effectively," according to Xiang.
</P>
<P>
State revenues have accounted for a greater portion of GDP in
recent years. Central authorities have effectively curbed
expenditures, and investments in education, science and
technology, grain reserve funds and poverty-stricken areas have
increased significantly, said Xiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
