<HEADLINE> U.S. Company to Help GCC States Link Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) Jamil Al-Hujailan Wednesday signed a
contract with the U.S. Hughes Company in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, to
link military radars of all GCC states.
</P>
<P>
GCC Assistant Secretary General for Military Affairs Major
General Faleh Abdallah Al-Shatti, who attended the signing
ceremony, told the Kuwait News Agency that "the cooperation belt
project" will take 26 months to be completed.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a cost of 85 million U.S. dollars, is aimed
at ensuring joint defense among GCC states by linking military
operation headquarters and air defense of all GCC states to
exchange data on radars and coordinate various operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The project is supplementary to the communication network
agreement signed by Al-Hujailan last December, which has been
carried out by the Swedish Ericsson Company at a cost of 70
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two projects were decided at the GCC summit held in Kuwait
last December.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
