<HEADLINE> NATO Urges Rugova to Resume Talks With Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana on Wednesday urged ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to resume
talks immediately with the Yugoslav government without conditions.
</P>
<P>
Solana delivered the message in a 30-minute meeting with ethnic
Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova at the NATO headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official, who declined to be named, quoted the NATO
chief as telling Rugova that ethnic Albanians' attempt to gain
Kosovo's independence from Belgrade was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary general made it clear to Rugova that he should
return to the negotiating table immediately without conditions and
resume the search for a negotiated solution," said the official.
</P>
<P>
Though the NATO did not support the status quo in Kosovo,
Solana said, the international community definitely did not
support independence for the breakaway province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The same NATO official said the 16-nation Western military
alliance favors "substantive autonomy" for the region.
</P>
<P>
Rugova, however, did not mention whether or when to resume
talks with Belgrade as he talked to the press after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Insisting that Kosovo had the right to become independent,
Rugova said he had asked NATO for "some kind of protection so
massive massacres and massive ethnic cleansing are prevented."
</P>
</TEXT>
