<HEADLINE> Pak PM Hopes to Meet With Indian Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif has sent a letter to his Indian counterpart, Atal Bihari
Vajpayee, hoping to discuss with him all issues between the two
countries in Colombo, Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Sharif expressed the hope that he and Vajpayee would hold a
meeting during the forthcoming summit of the South Asia
Association for Regional Cooperation in Colombo to discuss all
issues particularly issues of peace and security in the
nuclearized South Asia as well as the issue of Jammu and Kashmir,
the sole root cause of tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
The letter was sent on June 23, according to an official
statement issued Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Sharif referred to the Pakistani proposal made
on June 11 for the resumption of the dialogue between the two
countries on the agreed basis of June 23, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said a breakthrough between Pakistan and India on issues
of vital concern such as peace and security would open a new
chapter of cooperation and development in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with its constructive approach over the years for
resolving all outstanding issues between Pakistan and India, the
statement said, Islamabad has once again shown its readiness to
engage in a meaningful and result-oriented dialogue with India
aimed at finding an early settlement of the Jammu and Kashmir
issue in accordance with U.N. Security Council resolutions and the
aspirations of the Kashmiri people.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, Vajpayee sent a letter to Sharif and expressed his
hope to have a meeting with Sharif in Colombo. 
</P>
