<HEADLINE> China Vows to Strengthen Implementation of State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Auditor-General Li Jinhua today
called for strict supervision over implementation of the state
budget and tax collections.
</P>
<P>
Li, auditor-general of the National Audit Office, pointed out
that the lax taxation enforcement of many localities has burdened
the nation with heavy financial losses. Li made the remarks at
the third meeting of the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
"Judicial departments should punish law violators in this
regard in accordance with the revised Criminal Law," said Li.
</P>
<P>
All departments directly under the State Council must strictly
abide by the state budget and practice thrift, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his office will strengthen audits of bank
accounts opened by government departments, and added that "secret
accounts must be prohibited."
</P>
<P>
Budget implementation in 1997 was generally sound, said
Li. However, relevant departments should still standardize their
management over budgetary receipts and strictly implement
financial and tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
The National Audit Office has audited the central government
budget implementation for the past two years and the State Council
ordered related ministries to rectify all violations.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Taxation and the General
Administration of Customs collected overdue taxes totalling 3.3
billion yuan (400 million US dollars), with other departments
remitting an additional 1.96 billion yuan to taxation authorities.
</P>
<P>
The National Audit Office has also audited the operations of
relief funds of 592 poverty-stricken counties throughout the
country in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some poor counties have illegally used funds totalling 2.191
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Audit departments had recovered 810 million yuan in funds
misappropriated by poor counties by the end of 1997 and turned 17
corruption cases to judicial departments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
