<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Calls for Flood Control, Increased Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao, general
director of the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters, monitored the flood situation in east China's Fujian
and Jiangxi provinces and sent letters to the respective
provincial leaders on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He urged the two provinces to closely monitor weather and flood
conditions and prepare to protect important cities and towns,
railways and the property and well-being of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Wen stressed that the disaster relief effort should be expanded
and arrangements should be made for production and ensuring living
conditions for local residents.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have hit Fujian and Jiangxi since June 1, with
various parts of the two provinces hit by the heaviest flooding on
record, according to the flood control headquarters which today
sent telegrams to the areas expressing appreciation for related
flood relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Wen also urged that concrete measures should be adopted to
increase this year's agricultural output and maintain social
stability in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
During a fact-finding tour of north China's Hebei Province
between June 22-23, Wen said the nation's agricultural economy has
performed smoothly and noted that a good summer harvest has been
achieved despite severe natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that priority should be placed on the following
areas in order to increase the agricultural production and output
for the year:
</P>
<P>
-- Increasing this summer's area under cultivation, optimize
the planting structure, promoting the use of agro-technology and
preparing to control either severe flooding and droughts;
</P>
<P>
-- Implementing reform of the nation's grain marketing system
and protecting the enthusiasm of farmer for grain production by
purchasing all grain at subsidized prices and selling grain at
market prices;
</P>
<P>
-- Reducing burdens on farmers and increasing their income, and
serverly punishing those responsible for illegally increasing
related financial burdens. 
</P>
