<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions on Pakistan "Counterproductive": Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, JUNE 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina has expressed her appreciation of Pakistan's
position on nuclear tests, saying the sanctions imposed on
Pakistan in the wake of the tests are "counterproductive."
</P>
<P>
According to a Pakistani Foreign Ministry press release
Wednesday, Hasina, who arrived here on a one-day visit, made her
remarks during the formal talks with her Pakistani counterpart,
Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh prime minister said she did not approve of the
economic sanctions on Pakistan as "these are invariably
counterproductive."
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions would fail to promote the objectives of the
countries which imposed them," she added.
</P>
<P>
Hasina said she fully understood the compulsions that lay
behind Pakistan's decision to undertake the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
She further expressed apprehension at the prevailing tensions
which affected not only India and Pakistan but all countries in
the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Hasina informed Sharif, however, that India had clearly ruled
out the possibility of mediation by any third party in the process
of resolution of the Jammu and Kashmir dispute which is the sole
root cause of tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Sharif briefed Hasina on the grave security
threat faced by Pakistan as a result of India's nuclear tests,
saying that "in view of India's hostility Pakistan had no choice
but to exercise the nuclear option."
</P>
<P>
Sharif noted that the member states of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) desired to promote
mutual trust and understanding which are essential for the social
and economic uplift of this region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the agreement reached at the Ninth
SAARC Summit, that a process of informal political consultations
be instituted to promote mutual trust and understanding, would be
operationalized by the forthcoming SAARC summit in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Sharif underscored the need for an enabling environment of
peace and security which, he said, is "a sini qua non for the
exploitation of the full potential for economic cooperation in the
region."
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the P-5 (five permanent members) of the
U.N. Security Council and the G-8 have recognized the Jammu and
Kashmir dispute as the root cause of tension in the region which
must be addressed and resolved in accordance with U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Sharif stressed that Pakistan has always been prepared to enter
into a "meaningful dialogue" with India which would address in a
substantive and specific manner the question of peace and security
as well as the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, in view of the sterility of the bilateral dialogue it
is essential that the international community should remain
engaged in the process of facilitating a just solution to the
Kashmir dispute, Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
According to the press release, the two prime ministers
expressed their satisfaction at the state of their two countries'
relationship and exchanged views on measures needed to be taken to
further strengthen the ties.
</P>
<P>
During her stay here, Hasina was also received by President
Rafique Tarar.
</P>
<P>
Hasina, accompanied by Foreign Minister Abdul Samad Azad, was
the first foreign leader to have visited Pakistan since its
detonation of nuclear devices at the end of last month. Hasina
visited India last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
