<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Karachi Stock Exchange
(KSE)-100 Index Plunged Wednesday to its lowest level of 911.43
points on negative developments on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Wednesday, the lowest index recorded was 911.44 on
June 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The market opened Wednesday on a negative sentiment on news of
a fresh outbreak of violence in the southern port city in which
six members of the Karachi-based Muttehida Qaumi Movement party
were killed overnight.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by news that the government had decided not
to negotiate with the Hub Power Company management over the issue
of tariff reduction. Punters were hopeful before that discussion
between the government and the company would help resolve the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
News that the U.S.-based Parametric Fund has decided to
liquidate its 2 million U.S. dollar fund to Pakistan also affected
the sentiments in the already depressed market.
</P>
<P>
KSE Chairman Tasin Lakhani said the reason for the record low
at the KSE on Wednesday was the deteriorating law and order
situation in the city.
</P>
<P>
The KSE-100 Index dropped 56.24 points Wednesday to close at
911.43 against Tuesday's close of 967.67 points.
</P>
<P>
A total volume of 72.6 million shares was traded Wednesday
against 52.52 million shares traded in the previous trading day.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said they expect the market to recover slightly
Thursday as the bourse recovers from its new lows. 
</P>
