<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Remains Top of List for Luxury Goods: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong remains on top of the
list for shoppers seeking luxury goods at value-for-money prices,
according to the results of a recent survey on retail pricing of
luxury brand products in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted under the auspices of the Association of
Retail and Tourism Services (ARTS) by Duty Free Shops Group Ltd.,
focused on retail pricing of luxury brands throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
For the 12 brands covered in the survey, which include leather
goods, ready-to-wear clothing and cosmetics products, the overall
results reveal that, for most products surveyed, Hong Kong offers
shoppers lower prices than neighboring cities, with an average
price advantage of as much as 29 percent over Tokyo, 14 percent
over Bangkok, 12 percent over Seoul, 10 percent over Taipei and 2
percent over Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Jim Hurley, chairman of the ARTS, said there is a general
misconception that visitors to countries and regions suffering
from the effects of currency devaluation will be able to purchase
goods at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, while luxury brand vendors would normally review
their prices only once or at most twice a year, the currency
instability has forced vendors in some countries to adjust prices
upwards as many as three times over the past six months," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The survey results show that Hong Kong's competitive position
among major Asian cities for luxury brand-name merchandise looks
likely to be consolidated," Hurley said.
</P>
<P>
"These pricing benefits, combined with the widespread efforts
within the local retail industry to upgrade service and customer
care, mean that Hong Kong is now even more attractive as a
shopping destination," he declared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
