<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Firms in HK Confident of Future: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Over 90 percent of the foreign
companies in Hong Kong believe that their performance will be
positive over the next three years, a survey of business
confidence shows.
</P>
<P>
The survey, whose results were released here Wednesday, was
conducted by Hong Kong's international business community between
March and early June this year in the midst of the Asian financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that 80 percent of the 928 respondents
are positive about the Hong Kong business environment over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
The survey, titled "Business Survey'98," was carried out by
International Hong Kong, an informal group of 23 international
chambers of commerce and business associations in Hong Kong, in
cooperation with the Better Hong Kong Foundation (BHKF).
</P>
<P>
The survey sought to gauge the level of business confidence in
Hong Kong in view of the rapidly changing business environment in
the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
While a number of chambers of commerce and business
associations in Hong Kong regularly conduct surveys of their
members, this survey is the first comprehensive study of a large
cross-section of the international business community.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the results of the survey, BHKF's Chief Executive
George Yuen said this survey demonstrates that the international
business community takes a long-term view of economic
opportunities and development.
</P>
<P>
"The members of our business community know Hong Kong best.
They believe that Hong Kong will emerge from the current crisis
stronger than ever, as the case has been many times before," Yuen
continued.
</P>
<P>
Of the respondents, 70 percent listed Hong Kong as their
regional headquarters and 88 percent of those companies indicate
that they plan to maintain this status during the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two percent of respondent companies intend to expand
their operations in Hong Kong while 54 percent others plan to
maintain the current size of their operations.
</P>
<P>
Respondents attributed their confidence to Hong Kong's
strategic location, stable financial environment, productive
workforce and strong institutional fundamentals, including the
rule of law, independence of the judiciary and the free flow of
information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
