<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea: Imported Blood Plasma Contaminated With Hepatitis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Food and Drug
Administration said Wednesday some blood plasma imported from the
United States was found contaminated with the hepatitis C virus.
</P>
<P>
The finding, in five of the 270 blood plasma units taken as
inspection samples from an unidentified local pharmaceutical
company, prompted the government agency to take swift action.
</P>
<P>
As the samples were in a batch of 8,335 liters, or 21,000
packages, of blood plasma imported in April, the local company was
ordered to stop manufacturing blood products with the entire batch.
</P>
<P>
Under an investigation of the administration, including safety
inspection on 2,300 liters of unused plasma, the sampled units
were screened for HIV, hepatitis B and C and syphilis viruses.
</P>
<P>
The administration, however, acknowledged that the batch of
plasma in question was tested negative for the hepatitis virus
when it was shipped by a U.S. company into the country.
</P>
<P>
Blood plasma is used to make drugs, such as Albumin, for
patients with liver malfunction. If administered contaminated
products, chances are high that a patient will contract hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, some 60,000 liters of blood
plasma were transported into South Korea, mainly from the United
States and the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
