<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control Over Polluters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's top environmental official
said here today that China has taken strict measures on some
110,000 polluters over the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the State Environmental Protection
Administration, said at a news conference held by the Information
Office of the State Council that China spent more than 28 billion
yuan (3.37 billion US dollars) on controlling the pollution of
50,000-plus factories and shut down some 65,000 small plants with
serious pollution during the 1991-1997 period.
</P>
<P>
"China has scored remarkable achievements in pollution control
in its major valleys including the Huaihe river, Taihu and Dianchi
lake valleys. It had forced all the industrial polluters in the
Huaihe river valley to meet the discharge standards by the end of
last year," Xie said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a decline trend has occurred in the industrial
pollutants discharged by factories above the county level, and the
heavy metal pollution has been basically put under control thanks
to the effective measures adopted.
</P>
<P>
"Meanwhile, the daily average amount of the total suspended
particles in the air has lowered, and the environmental quality in
some cities has been improved," he added.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that in addition to increasing spending, China has
promulgated six laws on environmental protection and nine relevant
laws on resources protection.
</P>
<P>
"The clause of `crime against protection of environment and
resources' has been written into the amended Criminal Law," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
