<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review (1) by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China Strengthens Fiscal Macroeconomic Control Measures
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government recently
raised export tax rebates for five industries in a bid to promote
exports.
</P>
<P>
This move was one in a series of government fiscal measures the
government adopted in recent months as part of its effort
to stimulate the economy and reach this year's economic growth
target of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
China has gradually strengthened its use fiscal macroeconomic
control measures since the beginning of this year, while at the
same time continuing to focus on currency macro-controls in a bid
to reverse the declining trend in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Major fiscal measures include reducing the burdens requiring
enterprises to increase their usable capital; accelerating
government investment; improving the domestic investment
environment to attract more foreign capital; accelerating export
tax rebates; appropriately increasing the issuance of treasury
bonds to finance public utilities; and establishing a government
purchasing system.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance has abolished over 200 irrational fees
to alleviate the burden on enterprises, and for the first time
issued special treasury bonds valued at 45 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also largely expanded its investment budget in
a bid to guide enterprise, individual and foreign investment to
energy, transportation, telecommunications and various other
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
The railway construction budget has been raised from the
original 34.9 billion yuan to 45 billion yuan, and the highway
budget from 120 billion yuan to 160 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
