<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review China Adopts Fiscal Macroeonomic Control Measures (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng pointed out that China's
fiscal macroeconomic control effort offers great potential and
noted that good revenue growth mechanisms have been introduced
with an annual increase in revenue of over 100 billion yuan. He
added that the State Treasury's capability for guaranteeing
economic construction and social development has obviously been
improved.
</P>
<P>
However, he also pointed out that China's current fiscal
strength is subject to further development and noted there will be
limitations on the effects of fiscal macroeconomic control. Xiang
cautioned that fiscal measures should be carried out with prudence.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that the government should employ more fiscal
measures to support economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Zhiyun from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences said
that successfully controlling the overall economic scale will
require China to readjust its economic structure to adapt to
development of the market economy.
</P>
<P>
"Fiscal measures can play a significant role in controlling
resources and income distribution during the process of structural
readjustments," according to Zhao.
</P>
<P>
Economist Fan Gang said that government investment becomes the
key driving investment when considering the insufficiency of
related market investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Experts stress that currency policies must be combined with
fiscal measures to stimulate economic growth, and they note that
related measures are in most cases are a more effective means for
stimulating the economy. They suggest that the government pay
closer attention to fiscal measures when formulating new economic
policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
