<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Crashes to Become 3rd Largest Killer in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Road crashes will be the third
largest cause of death and disability worldwide in the next two
decades, according to a forecast released here Wednesday by the
International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
</P>
<P>
In countries like India and Mexico, road accidents may cost 2.5
billion to 3.2 billion U.S. dollars a year, said the "World
Disasters Report 1998," released here at a press conference by
Astrid Noklebye Heiberg, president of the Geneva-based
organization,.
</P>
<P>
"Road crashes hamper growth and progress by costing developing
countries the major chunk of the aid they receive," said Heiberg,
who is on a visit here.
</P>
<P>
She said road accidents are ahead of other major diseases like
respiratory infections, tuberculosis and HIV which get much more
attention.
</P>
<P>
The report said four-wheel vehicles increased by 23 percent to
4.5 million in India between 1990 and 1993 and the country will
have 267 million four-wheel vehicles on its roads by 2050 as
compared to the estimated 10 million now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
