<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Pelt Mogadishu, Killing 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Somali capital Mogadishu
and its neighboring region of Lower Shabelle are floating above
waters Wednesday as it started to pelt with heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The rain which started pouring at 2:00 am local time has
turned Mogadishu's streets into running rivers.
</P>
<P>
At least 22 people, mainly children, are known to have died
and 11 others wounded after their houses collapsed on top of them
in different areas in the capital Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As many as 100 houses are destroyed as a result of the heavy
rains in the districts of Huriwa, Bondhere, Yaqshid, Hodon, Hamar
Jajab, Hawlwadag and Wardhigley.
</P>
<P>
Groups of young volunteers have begun evacuating children and
the elderly from the water-threatened houses in various districts
early in the morning. Abdulaziz Mohamed Omar, one of the 30
volunteers who operated in Huriwa district of the capital said
they have rescued more than 80 children in 60 houses in their
area.
</P>
<P>
As the waters have created pools and lakes in Mogadishu,
thousands of families have fled their houses to the relatively
safer areas and to their well-off relatives for shelter and food.
</P>
<P>
The poorest built houses are those make-shift huts built for
the internally displaced refugees. At least one child had died
in the Trebunka refugee camp in Hodon district and most of the
one hundred huts are also washed away by the rain waters.
</P>
<P>
A two-story building in Hodon district and a chemist' in
Hararyalle area of the capital are also destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The rain has seriously affected the movement of the city by
making all the roads almost impassable. All public transport
buses, taxis and privately owned vehicles are out of circulation
in the capital Wednesday. Most of the markets are also closed
down due to the rains.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains were also reported in the port town of Merca, 100
km south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Faction leader Ali Mahdi Mohamed has called on the Somalis to
help each other at this crucial moment. He also appealed to the
international community to lead a helping hand to the Somalis.
</P>
<P>
This seasonal showers in the Deyr season has usually been
light, quick to pour and quick to let up, creating no problems.
It was in 1965 when the Deyr rains had been so heavy that
Mogadishu had been washed away by the waters, but the city was
not as large. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
