<HEADLINE> Hungarian PM Designate to Form Tripartite Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian prime minister
designate Orban Viktor signed on one more party Wednesday to form
a tripartite coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The latest ally of Viktor, of the Federation of Young
Democratic-Hungarian Civic Party (Fidesz-MPP), was the Independent
Small-holders' and Peasants' Party (ISPP).
</P>
<P>
A day before, for the same purpose, the right-wing leader
signed an agreement with the Hungarian Democratic Forum (HDF),
said a report of the Hungarian Telegraph Agency.
</P>
<P>
Under these arrangements, the eastern European country thus
will have a tripartite administration, with 12 cabinet seats going
to Fidesz-MPP, four to the ISPP and one to the HDF.
</P>
<P>
Holding different views on a range of issues, negotiations
between Fidesz-MPP and ISPP were quite tough. On one occasion,
Orban said he had no choice but to form coalition with the ISPP.
</P>
<P>
Orban's Fidesz-MPP won 148 out of the 386 seats of the
unicameral National Assembly, or parliament, in Hungary's
two-round legislative elections in May.
</P>
<P>
The ISPP and the HDF netted 48 and 17 seats respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
