<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China And Air Pollution Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China has worked out weekly air
pollution reports and worked to prevent sulphur dioxide emissions
and acid rain, according to Xie Zhenhua, director of the
State Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
He said today that 46 Chinese cities now issue a weekly report
on air pollution, and Beijing, Shanghai, and 3 others give daily
reports. Big cities like Beijing and Shanghai have begun to use
unleaded gas, and Hainan Island in southern China will become the
country's first province to ban the use of leaded gas.
</P>
<P>
China has stopped building coal-fired power plants in major
cities and controls the mining of coal with a sulphur content
greater than 3 percent, Xie says, explaining that these are some
of the measures to control air pollution in areas seriously
polluted by sulphur dioxide and acid rain, which fall on 11.4
percent of China's landmass.
</P>
<P>
Air pollution in China consists of smoke from burning coal with
sulphur dioxide, and smoky dust, and some 30 percent of China's
land area suffers from acid rain.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that less smokes were exhausted in China recent years,
but still more sulphur dioxide. In 1997, there was 18.7 million
tons of smoke particles emitted, a million less less than in 1995,
while 23.46 million tons of sulphur dioxide were exhausted, over a
million more than that in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guilin Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Guilin in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, is known for its scenery and history
which dates back more than 2,000 years to Qin Shihuang, founder of
the Qin Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The city, which covers 560 sq.km., hosts over 8.5 million
tourists annually, with most tourists coming from areas throughout
China.
</P>
<P>
Longsheng, Xing'an, Ziyuan, Sanjiang and Rongshui have been
designated close to Guilin as tourist areas offering the distinct
traditional practices and customs of ethnic minorities, typical
rural scenery, water conservancy, and temples which date back over
2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The city is undergoing a facelift which includes widening
narrow streets and bridges. Outdated brick, tile and wood
structures along the streets have been replaced by modern
buildings. Four large bridges cross the Lijiang River which
meanders through the city.
</P>
<P>
"We are in the process of building the Greater Guilin Tourist
Area which we hope to transform into a pioneering tourism-oriented
economic region," according to a senior local official.
</P>
<P>
Guilin has abundant water resources, with the Lijiang River
alone stretching some 426 kilometers and covering a drainage area
of 19,605 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Guilin enjoys a mild climate featuring a 309 day frost-free
period and is free of blistering heat in summer and extreme cold
in winter.
</P>
<P>
Favorable natural conditions make Guilin the ideal home for
gingko trees, clouded leopards, yellow-breasted tragopans,
pangolin, masket civets, giant salamanders and numerous other
species of flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
The city also features abundant mineral resources such as
bloodstone, talcose rock, lead, zinc, common pyrite and high
quality marble.
</P>
<P>
The tourist industry represents one of the most important
sectors in Guilin's economy.
</P>
<P>
The southern city has the capacity to host over one million
foreign and 10 million domestic tourists annually. A total of
400,000 local residents work in enterprises directly related to
tourism.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Guilin's tourism industry generates an
annual income of three billion yuan, or more than 15 percent of
the city's to GNP (gross national product).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Hits 141 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar jumped more than 2 yen
to top 141 yen temporarily in Tokyo on Wednesday as investors bought
dollars and sold yen because of continuing anxiety about Japan's
sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 140.34-37 yen at 5 p.m. (local time), up
from 139.60-62 yen at 9 a.m., and from 139.20-30 yen late Tuesday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said a definite bullishness for the dollar carried over
from overseas markets because of the market's skepticism that Japan
will act swiftly to shore up its economy.
</P>
<P>
After topping 140 yen, fears of intervention eased and market
players, particularly Japanese institutional investors, pushed the
U.S. currency over 141 yen, they said.
</P>
<P>
But a late afternoon wave of dollar-selling pushed the dollar back
below 140 yen and sparked market players to square their currency
positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
