<HEADLINE> China's Top Legislature Discusses Village Committee Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China's National People's Congress
is discussing a law that guarantees the rights of 900 million
farmers to deal with present-day problems in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Today, members of the Ninth NPC's Standing Committee discussed
the Organic Village Committee Law, which has been tried out for a
decade.
</P>
<P>
It allows villagers to directly elect village leaders,
something that was unheard of before the 1980s. It also provides
for the public availability of village financial affairs,
construction plans, and land contracts.
</P>
<P>
Feng Zhijun said that "democratic rights" specified in the law
need to be stated more specifically and that village committees
should be chosen by democratic election and major affairs settled
after villagers' opinions are sought.
</P>
<P>
The content of village affairs and the democratic supervision
by villagers should also be specifically stated, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li Wenquan, the vice-chairman of the Shandong Provincial
People's Congress Standing Committee, said that supervisory rules
should be included in the law for greater supervision of village
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Bai Shangwu, of the NPC Agriculture and Rural Affairs
Committee, said that the law should reduce farmers' burdens.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee plans to further standardize the
democratic management of village affairs in China's nearly one
million villages. According to Civil Affairs Ministry sources,
more than 900,000 villages have had three direct elections in the
past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
