<HEADLINE> Iran Need to Beat Germany to Qualify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTPELLIER, France, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran have to beat former
world champion Germany in Mosson Stadium here Thursday evening in
order to have a chance of reaching last 16 in the World Cup finals for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians took streets to celebrate back home after Jalal
Talebi's squad defeated the United States 2-1 on Sunday, but their
opponent this time was not ordinary side.
</P>
<P>
Having won the cup three time before, the Germans showed their
unparralled experience and fighting spirit by rallying from two goals
down to tie Yugoslavia 2-2.
</P>
<P>
Talebi said, "If we beat Germany there will be an even bigger party
back home."
</P>
<P>
It is of course Iran's best bet to stake their hope on the three
players who know Germany well.
</P>
<P>
Striker Ali Daei and midfielder Karim Bagheri play for Arminia
Bielefeld while Khodad Azizi is with FC Cologne.
</P>
<P>
Striker Azizi said, "If we want to go through to the second round
we have to beat Germany. Nothing is impossible in this world."
</P>
<P>
They will also hope the attacking midfieler Mehdi Mahdavikia,
scorer of the second goal against the Americans, will bring luck again
to the Middle East country.
</P>
<P>
Germany, who need only a draw to go through, have taken discretion
by fielding a much older line-up in a game they could not afford to
lose.
</P>
<P>
Lothar Matthaeus, 37, has shown his value again in his fifth finals
when he turned the game around against Yugoslavia as a second-half
substitute and is expected to start against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Matthaeus, who came on as a substitute against Yugoslavia and
helped turn the match around, will extend his record of World Cup
games to 23. He is expected to take on the libero role with Thon
moving into midfield.
</P>
<P>
More experienced Olaf Thon and Thomas Helmer may start in replace
of the younger Dietmar Hamann and Jens Jeremies.
</P>
<P>
Germany have only once failed to get past the first round in 1938
when the tournament was last held in France.
</P>
<P>
Coach Berti Vogts is likely to field a team with only three players
under 30 in Michael Tarnat, Joerg Heinrich and Christian Woerns.
</P>
<P>
He said, "I was forced to change things around against Yugoslavia
because the performances from some of the players were not good,"
Vogts said. "I know certain players have a mental problem. I know who
I can rely on." 
</P>
</TEXT>
