<HEADLINE> Singapore's Helicopter Deal Yet to Be Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Defense of
Singapore stated Wednesday that no deal has yet been struck with
anyone on its much-reported helicopter purchase.
</P>
<P>
Tenders were still being evaluated and one of the top
contenders is the type of the American-made Apache attack
helicopter, the ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Reuters reported that Singapore wanted
to buy American-made military helicopters, missiles and other
high-tech aircraft equipment worth 620 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has been trying to upgrade the equipment of its Armed
Forces and an earlier report said the Defense Ministry might
complete the market survey of attack helicopters and make an
announcement by the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the U.S.-made Apache and South
African-made Rooivalk were in close race for the profitable deal.
</P>
<P>
One of the AH-64d Apache type, which is armed with an array of
sophisticated missiles, rockets and automatic cannons and can be
used as frontline "tank busters" and reconnaissance platforms, was
flown to Singapore and displayed at Paya Lebar Air Base for
special demonstration in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Rooivalk is also a type of high-tech attack helicopter.
Singapore's Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defense Tony
Tan Keng Yam inspected the Rooivalk type in November 1997 when he
visited south Africa. 
</P>
