<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Works to Ease Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China is extending great effort to
ease pollution problems, especially air pollution in Beijing, at
the earliest possible date, according to Xie Zhenhua, director of the
State Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's press conference sponsored by the State
Council Information Office, Xie said the Chinese capital will
reduce pollution resulting from the use of coal by adjusting its
energy structure, promoting the use of high quality coal and
expanding the use of central heating systems.
</P>
<P>
He said that management of construction sites in the city will
be improved and the use of mechanized street cleaners and water
trucks will be expanded to reduce dust in the air.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will use over 700 million sq.m. of natural gas by the
2000 in order to improve the local energy structure, said Xie.
</P>
<P>
Beijing will tackle exhaust emissions by tightening controls
over motor vehicles, both in terms of the market and actual use.
Automobiles failing to meet emission standards will not be
allowed to enter the market, and vehicles already in use will be
required to install emission control equipment. In addition, the
city will closely monitor the system for junking old vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"Beijingers have expressed dissatisfaction with the air
quality," said Xie. "However, I firmly believe that existing
measures and other control plans set for implementation will
improve the air quality."
</P>
<P>
He said that moving the Capital Iron and Steel Group, widely
recognized as one of the major polluters in the capital, is
unfeasible due to the size of the enterprise. However, the group's
production scale will be controlled to reduce pollution discharge
levels. Nearby power plants will also be required to reduce
pollution levels.
</P>
<P>
Beijing ranks at the top of the list of Chinese cities with air
pollution problems, with main problems centering on the total
volume of suspended particles, sulphur dioxide and nitrogen oxide.
</P>
<P>
The city's normal air quality is rated at the third level
(light pollution) and sometimes drops to the fourth level (medium
pollution), according to weekly air quality reports of major
Chinese cities released by China Environmental Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to raise the city's air quality to the second level
within five years, but will require substantial funding to do so,"
said Xie, adding that the municipal government has adopted a goal
for controlling pollution within five years and has assigned
experts to draft the city's long-term environmental protection
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Australian Graduates Fail Literacy Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Up to half of Australian
university graduates failed literacy tests given by prospective
employers, a new study has found.
</P>
<P>
Graduates who achieved quite acceptable results in their
university course were being pulled up for poor use of grammar and
inadequate spelling, the AAP Wednesday quoted a report on the
study as saying.
</P>
<P>
AC Nielsen Research Services, which conducted the study for the
federal government, warned in the report that the failure of
graduates to maintain decent literacy standards was costing them
jobs.
</P>
<P>
"It is disturbing to reflect that, according to anecdotal
evidence, up to half of graduates who are achieving adequate
academic results can be rejected by employers after testing for
literacy and numeracy," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Poor use of grammar is one complaint by employers, while
inadequate spelling is another. Use of word processors has led to
reliance on them, but this can lead in practice to the
substitution of quite the wrong word in context."
</P>
<P>
Numeracy was less of a problem but there were concerns that use
of calculators had removed the ability to do even simple mental
arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
The Research on Employer Satisfaction with Graduate Skills
interim report was based on group discussions with employers,
government recruiters, industry associations and graduates.
</P>
<P>
The skills sought in graduates included literacy, numeracy,
time management skills, written business communication skills,
inter-personal skills and problem solving skills.
</P>
<P>
But literacy, numeracy and computer skills should have mostly
been developed at school and not university.
</P>
<P>
"Employers are concerned at the decline of basic skills, such
as oral and written communication and numeracy, and directly
relate this deficiency to declining standards of education," the
report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
