<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Arafat Accepts Entire Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat Wednesday avoided a no-confidence
motion against his cabinet in the legislative council by
announcing the mass resignation of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
A new administration will be formed within two weeks, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) Wednesday decided to
cancel a no-confidence vote against Arafat's cabinet, said a PLC
statement faxed to Xinhua from Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The PLC had scheduled to discuss the no-confidence vote on
Thursday over the alleged corruption by a number of PNA ministers
and the poor performance of their ministries.
</P>
<P>
The council decision was made after PLC Speaker Abu Ala
received a letter from Arafat announcing the resignation of the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"The resignations of all ministers have been accepted and
consultations (on forming a new cabinet) are still going on and a
list of the new government members will be presented to the PLC
within two weeks," Arafat said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Several PLC members had threatened to launch a no-confidence
vote against Arafat's cabinet last year, charging there were
corruptions by some cabinet ministers and mismanagement of their
ministries.
</P>
<P>
The accusations against the cabinet gathered momentum by the
end of last May, as 28 PLC members submitted a motion to the PLC,
urging Arafat to reform his administration or face a no-confidence
vote in the PLC.
</P>
<P>
These lawmakers also accused the cabinet for its delay and
unreasonable allocations of the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
The PLC decided on May 31 to give two weeks' time to Arafat to
reshuffle his cabinet and resubmit the budget to the PLC for
consideration with changes as asked by the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Facing the charges from the PLC, Arafat decided to reshuffle
his cabinet and on June 15, he asked the PLC to give him 10 more
days to finish this work.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Arafat started his political consulations with
leaders of other Palestinian parties and factions over the issue
of the cabinet reshuffle, even asking them to join the new
administration as part of the national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's political consulations have received wide support from
the other political factions, which they believe could help all
parties concerned to form a united front against Israeli
occupation and realize the Palestinians' right of
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Arafat in his letter asked for two more weeks to fulfill his
task and conduct more consulations with other parties.
</P>
<P>
But foreign diplomats here pointed out the it is hard for
Arafat to form a multi-party administration because other parties
do not support the peace process and the Oslo Accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
