<HEADLINE> Interview: "One Country, Two Systems" Working Well: Indian Chamber Leader By Feng Xiuju </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- "One country, two systems" has
been working well in Hong Kong since it returned to China last
July, says M. Arunachalam, chairman of the Indian Chamber of
Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua at his office here,
Arunachalam said the past one-year practice shows that the concept
 of "one country, two systems" is "good and practicable."
</P>
<P>
Arunachalam, who has been doing business in Hong Kong for more
than 20 years, said that before Hong Kong returned to China, many
people doubted whether this concept would be implemented or not,
but now, nobody is worried about it because Hong Kong is operating
well.
</P>
<P>
The Central government follows a non-interference policy
towards the government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I would say without the least hesitation that the Central
Government of China has scrupulously adhered to the concept of
'one country, two systems'.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong has certainly been governed by Hong Kong people
since July 1997. It remains a city with a free economic policy,
good infrastructure and communications, and convenient
transportation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The recent Hong Kong Legislative Council elections have
further reinforced this process and I am confident the people of
Hong Kong will be left free by the Central Government to rule
themselves in the years to come," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
