<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Cuts Fleet Size </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL),
struggling through the gravest financial crisis in its 57-year
history, has been forced to reduce its fleet size from 54 to 14
aircraft, a senior PAL officer said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a must for us to dispose of our excess aircraft if we
are to survive," said PAL chief financial officer Jaime Bautista.
"It makes no sense for us to keep paying lease charges on these
airplanes if we are not using them."
</P>
<P>
Bautista said PAL will pre-terminate leases on 27 airplanes and
sell off 13 other aircraft it owns as part of a rehabilitation
plan to nurse the ailing flag carrier back to financial health.
</P>
<P>
PAL currently leases 30 of the 54 aircraft in its fleet, for
which it pays about 30 million U.S. dollars a month in lease
charges.
</P>
<P>
However, Bautista said PAL did not expect to realize a gain
from the disposal of its own aircraft. "We expect the proceeds
from the sale to just be enough to service our obligations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
PAL went into a financial tailspin when its 620-strong pilots
went on strike nearly three weeks ago. The work stoppage brought
a daily loss of 150 million pesos (3.75 million U.S. dollars) to
PAL.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, our daily collections are not even enough to cover
variable expenses. On top of this, we have fixed expenses of 60
million pesos (1.5 million dollars) a day, which we still have to
pay for even if we don't operate," Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the rehabilitation plan the airline submitted to
the Securities and Exchange Commission on June 19 was the only
hope for PAL to stay aloft. The commission has formed a five-man
committee to oversee the rehabilitation program for the flag
carrier.
</P>
<P>
The proposed plan calls for, among others, a significant
reduction in fleet size, disposal of excess assets, restructuring
of the route network, lay-off of personnel, outsourcing of some
airline functions, giving up routes and frequencies to strategic
alliances and obtaining the support of creditors and unions.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to fully implement all the various elements of
the rehabilitation plan. If one of the elements is missing, the
entire plan will be unsuccessful," Bautista said.
</P>
<P>
PAL has already obtained the support of its creditor banks, who
have agreed to reschedule the airline's debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
