<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea, who is yet to win a single
match in the soccer World Cup finals after qualifying for four
consecutive times, will attempt to salvage some pride when they face
Belgium at Parc des Princes on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A 5-0 loss to the Netherlands on Satuday doused their hope to reach
the last 16 and led to the sacking of coach Cha Bum Kun, but
replacement coach Kim Pyong-Sok is expected to play a more attacking
game.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to make some changes, we're going to reinforce the
midfield and both flanks because the Belgians are likely to take
advantage of any weaknesses there," said Kim.
</P>
<P>
Pohang Steeler's teenager striker Lee Dong Gook, known as "Ronaldo
of Korea", may lead the attack with Choi Yong Soo.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Belgium needs to repeat their 2-0 over the
Koreans in the 1990 finals in Italy in order to qualify for the last
16 here.
</P>
<P>
But their fate is not entirely in their own hands, as they have to
pray that Dutch neighbours should beat Mexico.
</P>
<P>
If the Netherlands tie Mexico, Belgium must win by at least three
goals to go through.
</P>
<P>
Belgium has two points after two draws, two points behind the group
leaders Dutches and Mexicans both at four points.
</P>
<P>
Much will rely on Enzo Scifo to create opportunities for strikers
Luc Nilis and Luis Oliveirar and midfielder Marc Wilmots, the scorer
of both goals in the 2-2 draw against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Nico Van Kerckhoven will replace injured winger Danny Boffin while
goalkeeper Filip De Wilde is an injury doubt with a groin strain and
coach Geroge Leekens may have to play Philippe Van De Walle.
</P>
<P>
Veteran captain Franky Van der Elst is also doubtful. 
</P>
