<HEADLINE> Tanzania Joins Five Intellectual Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has joined five
intellectual property treaties of two international organizations
to keep pace with the trade globalization and protect its
manufactures from both internal and external infringements.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from the Ministry of Industries and Trade
said these treaties are the Nice (France) Agreement concerning
the international classification of goods and services for the
purpose of registration of marks, the Patent Cooperation Treaty
(PCT) of 1970 and the Madrid Agreement concerning the
international registration of marks of the World Intellectual
Property Organization (WIPO), Stephen Mtetewaunga, the acting
registrar with department of registrations, commercial laws and
industrial licensing, has said.
</P>
<P>
The other two are the Harare Protocol on Patent and
Industrial Design and the Banjul Protocol on Marks of 1993 of the
African Regional Industrial Property Organization (ARIPO), local
press reports quoted Mtetewaunga as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
By adopting these treaties, Mtetewaunga said, Tanzanian
manufacturers could register their goods in any member country by
using one language and registration fee.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania must reform various intellectual property laws under
the trade related aspects of intellectual property (TRIPS)
agreement which is part of the World Trade Organization (WTO)
conventions of 1994," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mtetewaunga explained the reasons for delaying to adopt the
treaties as financial constraints as the government was not
setting up funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries to Launch Anti-Malaria Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 46 African countries will
launch a new initiative next year, aiming at reducing illnesses
and deaths due to malaria, the Guardian newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new initiative, tagged "African initiative for malaria
control in the 21st century (AIM)", is the brainchild of the
World Health Organization (WHO) African Region.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to reduce to the barest minimum mortality and
morbidity associated with malaria over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate goal of the program is to ensure that by the year
2030, "malaria will neither be the major contributor to mortality
and morbidity nor of significant socio-economic consequence", the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the initiative is designed to reduce illnesses
and deaths resulting from malaria by 50 percent by the year 2010,
30 percent by 2015 and by another 20 percent by 2025.
</P>
<P>
The key features of the implementation of the initiative will
be early treatment of malaria cases, promotion of the use of
insecticide and impregnated nets, prevention, detection or
containment of epidemics, and strengthening of the capacities of
countries and communities to combat the disease.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is the leading health problem in Africa, and the
sub-Sahara region in particular. Almost all the 550 million
people in the region run the risk of malaria.
</P>
<P>
The disease, according to WHO, attacks between 270 and 480
million people and kills between 1.5 and 2.7 million in the world
yearly.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the direct and indirect losses due to
malaria in the region rose from 800 million U.S. Dollars in 1987
to more than 2,000 million U.S. Dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
