<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Airport Controls Bird Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Macao International Airport has
adopted a series of measures to reduce possible bird strike on
planes, and bird appearance near the airport has become evidently
rare.
</P>
<P>
Rui Balaco, vice-chairman of the Civil Aviation Authority of
Macao, told Xinhua in a recent interview that bird presence at the
 airport has dropped substantially since the beginning of this
year after the airport and the authority took "active" and
"passive" measures.
</P>
<P>
As an active measure, the airport has installed five gas
cannons since late last year along the runway of the airport,
which was built on land reclaimed from sea. The cannons fire
automatically at intervals to drive birds away. The airport is
also buying electronic devices that can flare sounds to frighten
birds away.
</P>
<P>
The "passive" measures include stepped-up cleaning at the
airport, keeping garbage and passenger disposals away from birds,
which were often attracted to look for food. The airport also
trims the lawn around the runway at a certain height so that birds
cannot hide in it.
</P>
<P>
In addition, at times when migratory birds flock, the airport
sent out patrol vehicles to drive them away. This measure was
described by Balaco as "most effective."
</P>
<P>
All these measures have been proved effective for a certain
period of time, but no single method can produce long-term effects
as desired, said Balaco.
</P>
<P>
"The gas cannons, for instance, are good for the migration
birds, but not so useful for the resident birds because they get
used to it," said Balaco. "The ideal is all these measures working
together."
</P>
<P>
Inaugurated in November 1995, the airport has reported three
incidents of bird strikes, with two serious ones, inflicting
damage to the engines.
</P>
<P>
Bird strike on planes is a universal problem at all airports
around the world. It can cause serious damage to the plane engines
if the striking bird is large and hits the plane during taking
off, said Balaco.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
