<HEADLINE> HKSAR Takes Measures to Promote Film Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government announced a package of
measures to promote the further development of film industry as
the Hong Kong International Film Market (FILMART '98) opened here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the event's opening ceremony at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center, Secretary for Information
Technology and Broadcasting Kwong Ki Chi said that the SAR
government would work in parallel to simplify government
procedures by such measures as cutting bureaucratic red tapes and
making it easier for film crews to obtain the necessary approvals
to do location shooting.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council, the
three-day FILMART '98 is supported by the Hong Kong, Kowloon &AMP; New
Territories Motion Picture Industry Association Ltd. and the Movie
Producers and Distributors Association of Hong Kong Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said that Hong Kong is still as dynamic and as open as
ever. "Out 6.5 million people continue to enjoy the freedom of
speech and of the press. Out film-makers and film distributors
continue to make and show films of their liking and choice," he
said.
</P>
<P>
A Film Services Advisory Committee comprising leading
personalities from the film industry and other supporting
organizations had been set up to support the continuing growth of
the film industry, Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
The event has attracted 62 film and television companies from
Australia, Canada, Mexico, Britain, the United States and China's
mainland, Hong Kong and Taiwan. 
</P>
