<HEADLINE> 6 Species of "Kima" Found in Indonesia's Irian Jaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Researchers of the World Wide Fund
for Nature (WWF) have found six species of the "kima," a kind of
marine biota, in Indonesia's Irian Jaya, Antara News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The researchers have found the species at the Teluk Cendrawasih
Marine Park in Manokwari, about 360 kilometers west of Jayapura,
capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
This makes the marine park one of the world's parks with the
largest number of marine biota species, head of the park Minto
Basuki was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The researchers also found several turtle species in the park,
Basuki added.
</P>
<P>
Data from the WWF show that Indonesia has seven turtle species,
four of which are thriving in the waters of northern Irian Jaya.
</P>
