<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hong Kong's Financial System Withstands Regional Turmoil (1) by Wang Qun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- While the regional financial
turmoil is dragging the Hong Kong economy into a painful phase of
adjustment, the well-established Hong Kong banking and financial
system has stood firm in the severe test.
</P>
<P>
And the linked exchange rate, the cornerstone of Hong Kong
monetary and financial stability, has been well preserved, making
the Hong Kong dollar the only freely convertible currency in the
region that has survived unscathed in the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Prudent macro-economic policies, a rule-based monetary system,
a sound regulatory framework and robust financial infrastructure
are viewed as the best guarantee for the stability of the Hong
Kong dollar, while the mainland authorities' clear commitment of
not to devaluate Renminbi lending a forceful support to the local
currency.
</P>
<P>
However, mounting evidence showed that the year 1998 will be a
very difficult one for Hong Kong banks, which have to contend with
the blows to confidence from continuing regional upheavals, most
recently the political unrest in Indonesia and the weak Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with an economic slowdown -- as indicated by a negative
GDP growth for the first quarter of this year, "it is not
surprising that the banks in Hong Kong are going through more
difficult times," said David Carse, deputy chief executive of the
Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), when addressing the impact
of the regional financial turmoil on Hong Kong banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"The severity of the Asian crisis is a once-in-a-lifetime event
and no banking system in the region can hope to be unaffected by
it. There is bound to be an impact on the banks' funding and
liquidity, loan growth, asset quality and ultimately their
profitability," Carse told a conference on Pacific Basin business,
economics and finance in May.
</P>
<P>
The combination of regional difficulties and domestic slowdown
inevitably led to some deterioration in asset quality. In the
first quarter of the year there was a noticeable rise in loans
overdue for more than 3 months. But as a percentage of total
loans, the figure for the local banks -- less than 2 percent -- is
still reasonable by international, let alone, regional standards.
</P>
<P>
Further deterioration can be expected in the coming months,
although not to the extent seen in other parts of Asia, Carse
said. However, even deterioration occurs, banks have very
substantial protection from continued operation profits, existing
bad debt provisions, collateral and high capital adequacy ratios.
</P>
<P>
It is important to keep in mind that the local banks are still
making money so far this year, though generally lower against
1997. "While lower profitability is by no means welcome, it is
not, by itself, a cause for concern in terms of the stability of
the banking system," Carse noted.
</P>
<P>
"The year 1998 will be a tough year, but I am confident that
the banks have the fundamental capital strength to manage their
way through it," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0143 </DOCNO>
