<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>    He observed that "opportunities (rising from the crisis) are waiting to be uncovered and developed." </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At a time when Southeast Asian economies have suffered a
setback and will take a few years to recover, Hong Kong can make
itself an even more important business and financial center, said
Davies, who is also Standard Chartered Bank's group executive
director for Hong Kong, China and Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland is drawing lessons from the regional
crisis seriously and major reforms are being implemented. "These
are going to open up new business opportunities for Hong Kong,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of Hong Kong's flexibility and dynamism, a
pro-business environment, and a strong, capital-intensive and
orderly institutional framework, all of which are "grounds for
optimism" that Hong Kong will emerge stronger from the storm.
</P>
<P>
And the banking system "forms an integral part of this
institutional setup" and "has proved itself as one of the most
trustworthy pillars of the local economy," Davies noted.
</P>
<P>
"The strength of the banking system in Hong Kong is also a key
factor underlying the territory's resilience in the face of the
strains of the Asian turmoil," Davies stressed.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that his association, grouping all the licensed banks
in Hong Kong, will continue to work closely with the authorities
to ensure that the banking system remains sound and stays ahead of
developments in international financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The strength of Hong Kong financial system got recognition of
the regional and international community. The June 2 edition of
the Asian Wall Street Journal commented: "As the Asian doom and
gloom spreads, it is important to remember that Hong Kong is a
thriving financial center, not a domino. Its physical and human
infrastructure makes it one of the world's premier places to
conduct business. The banking sector is fundamentally sound and
the currency stable. On top of that there's Hong Kong's role and
potential as banker to the juggernaut next door: China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
