<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Consumer Inflation Rises in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's annual
consumer inflation increased to 5.1 percent in May from five
percent in April, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figures released Tuesday by the Central Statistical
Service show that month-on-month rise in the consumer price index
(CPI) was 0.4 percent from April.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the inflation rate was in line with
market expectations, but this could be the last good figure
before a sharp rise next month because of an increase in mortgage
rates.
</P>
<P>
The index, which tracks the price of a typical basket of
goods, was hiked mainly by an unexpected sharp increase in food
prices of 0.8 percent, resulting in year-on-year food inflation
being slightly higher at 6.7 percent.  
</P>
