<HEADLINE> S. Africa Saves World's Oldest Footprints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has removed the
world's oldest human footprints from a lagoon and airlifted them
to safety, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "Eve's Footprints", the 117,000-year-old fossil was
moved Tuesday to the South African Museum in Cape Town to protect
against vandalism as well as erosion.
</P>
<P>
Resin was poured into the fragile sandstone and allowed to
dry. A highly-powered diamond drill cut a portion of the rock
away. And the fossil was encased in an aluminium box.
</P>
<P>
The fossil was discovered last year in the Langebaan lagoon,
about 80 kilometers northwest of Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The footprints are believed to be those of a woman, dubbed
"Eve" by scientists because of the growing belief that humans had
their origin in south or southwestern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Only four such footprints were discovered so far in the world,
all in Africa, according to South African Broadcasting
Corporation (SABC) television.
</P>
<P>
Scientists hope that more prints could be found in the
vicinities of the lagoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
