<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Push Through Tourism Program in DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will push through an
agreed tourism development project of Mountain Kumgangput in the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea(DPRK) despite a submarine
incident, said a spokesman of South Korean President Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government's policy of separating economic
issues from politics is of mutual benefit to both sides of the
Korean peninsula, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
During his eight-day visit to DPRK, Chung Ju-yung, South Korean
Hyundai Group's founder, reached an agreement last week with the
DPRK to develop tourism resources of Mountain Kumgang by bringing
1,000 South Korean tourists every day to the mountain area
beginning from September this year.
</P>
<P>
However, one day before Chung's formal announcement of the
tourism agreement, a DPRK submarine was caught by South Korea
after it was found entangled in a fishing dragnet some 11 miles
off South Korean northeastern city Sokcho.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK's Korean Central News Agency said Tuesday the small
sub was wrecked while on a training mission and DPRK was searching
for the vessel and its crew.
</P>
<P>
But, the South Korean military authorities said the sub was
infiltrating into its waters and it was drifting there due to
engine failure as the DPRK described.
</P>
<P>
South Korean opposition Grand National Party, the majority in
the parliament, urged the government to dismiss
Defense Minister Chun Yong-taek for his "inadequate response" in
dealing with the sub incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
