<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Nigerian Troops in Liberia Move to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian contingent to the west
African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) has begun to pull out from
Liberia into Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to lead to the anticipated relocation of
the ECOMOG headquarters from Monrovia, capital of Liberia, to the
Sierra Leonean capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military said that the pull-out was to beef up
the troop strength in Freetown to flush out elements of the
ousted military junta and allied rebels.
</P>
<P>
However, sources said the departure of the Nigerian troops in
Monrovia is also connected with the continued tension between the
peacekeepers and the State Security Services (SSS) of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Relations between ECOMOG and Liberian President Charles Taylor
have been sour for sometimes as the warlord-turn president has
reportedly asked the force to leave his country after it helped
him gain the power.
</P>
<P>
Confrontations between ECOMOG and SSS men who are also known
as the bodyguards of Taylor also happened repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
The latest took place last Sunday night when a SSS man
refused to allow the passenger vehicle he was in to be searched
by ECOMOG soldiers at a checkpoint in Monrovia, according to
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Timothy Shelpidi.
</P>
<P>
The SSS men's attack against an ECOMOG soldier led to
hostilities between the soldiers and a group of 30 SSS men who
came later, the commander said, quoted by the British
Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force has complained to the government but
the government has said nothing, the report said.
</P>
<P>
West African leaders sent ECOMOG to Liberia in 1990 to help
end the bloody civil war in that country. The force created
security for the country's first post-war election last year,
with Taylor becoming the president.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG also interfered in the situation in Sierra Leone after
a coup ousted the country's civilian government in May last year.
It overthrew the junta last February and is mopping up the
remnants in the eastern and northern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the biggest contributor to ECOMOG, has about 6,000
troops in Sierra Leone which will be joined by more soldiers from
other west African countries, according to Nigeria's defense
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Chiefs of Defense Staff meeting held in Accra,
Ghana, last April "identified that about 10,000 troops would be
needed" to flush out the remnants of Sierra Leone's junta and
allied rebels, said Godwin Ugbo, acting director of defense
information Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, Gambia and Nigeria are among countries which have
pledged to contribute more troops in support of ECOMOG's cause,
according to Ugbo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Volkswagen Gearing Up for Increased Business In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The world's 4th largest automobile
manufacturer, Germany's Volkswagen AG, will accelerate development
in China by increasing cooperation with Chinese partners, building
an effective sales system, and improving research and development
here.
</P>
<P>
Stefan Jacoby, vice-president of VW's Asia-Pacific Region, said
at a news conference here Tuesday that this will help Volkswagen
maintain its lead in China in sedan market share, and will help
the group reach its goal of turning its joint ventures in China
into multi-functional companies that can compete globally.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the group had sold 1.3 million cars in
China. Volkswagen's two joint ventures in China -- in the cities
of Shanghai and Changchun -- occupy more than half of China's car
market.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Volkswagen's sales are expected
to rise 7.1 percent from the same period of 1997, to 153,000, or
58 percent of the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, Chinese clients have much higher expectations and
greater wants than before, and are catching up to people in the
West, Jacoby said, and a more efficient sales system in China is
the key to a successful business.
</P>
<P>
A VW-funded automobile research and development center is
expected to be built at a cost of one billion yuan (120 million US
dollars), next year in Shanghai. The center will meet the growth
needs of China's automobile industry and is expected to boost
Volkswagen's presence in China, he says.
</P>
<P>
China's automobile industry is changing from a seller's to a
buyer's market and Volkswagen will develop new car customers in
China and pay special attention to the rapidly-growing number of
private car buyers, Jacoby added.
</P>
<P>
Private owners account for 22 percent of China's car buyers at
present, in contrast to 15 percent three years ago.
</P>
<P>
At the ongoing 5th Beijing International Automotive Industry
Exposition, Volkswagen, along with Audi and Skoda, has a
full-range of products on display, including its Passat, Golf, and
Sharan brands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
