<HEADLINE> One in Five Namibian Adults HIV Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 24 (Xinhua) -- About 20 percent of Namibian
adults between the ages of 15 and 49 are infected with the HIV
virus, a United Nations report said.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS report, to be presented at the United Nations' 12th
World AIDS Conference in Geneva next week, says that 150,000
people in Namibia are HIV positive, the South African Press
Association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS country program director, Mary Delaney, said that
HIV/AIDS is the single most important macroeconomic variable for
the country for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The cost of hundreds of sick people and their eventual deaths
would overwhelm the country's health care system, Delaney
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Namibia was ranked among the top 10 AIDS-infected countries in
a report by the Namibian Health Ministry in December, 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
