<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder for President's Clinton's China Trip: Shanghai: Simultaneous "Dialogue" with International Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) - Shanghai is able to be in
simultaneous "dialogue" with the international business world,
from trade to financial industry, said Minmin Zhong, president of
the U.S. CitiBank Shanghai Branch in explaining why the firm chose
to move its China area headquarters here from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the debut of the Pudong Economic Development
Zone heralded the integration of the Chinese economy with the
world.
</P>
<P>
The city's infrastructure ranging from transportation and
energy to communications have transformed the skyline in the last
decade. Most of the pilot programs authorizing foreign banks to
engage in the Chinese currency yuan-based business and other
financial reforms in China have been initiated in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
It is not only China's largest manufacturing base, but also is
becoming an international financial and trade center.
</P>
<P>
In this tiny portion of China's territory, 145 million
U.S. dollars worth of goods are exported every day; 7.58 billion
yuan (about 913 million U.S. dollars) of stocks are traded; and
nearly 10,000 people enter or leave China daily.
</P>
<P>
It is now a hub of domestic and international monetary,
commodity, technology, human resources and information movements.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's economic strength is its foundation for its
"dialogue" with the world economy.
</P>
<P>
"Shanghai is the key to modern China," a professor at the
University of Maryland prophesied nearly 40 years ago. The saying
is now being validated by financial brokers and industrialists
from throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Half of the globe's top 100 companies have investments in
Shanghai. Under such a strong influence, Shanghai is now playing
host to 17,500 overseas-funded businesses with contracted
investment exceeding 30 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the top 50 banks in the world, 80 percent have branch
offices in the city. Total assets of foreign financial
institutions add up to 17.51 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac led a trade mission to Shanghai
last year that he called the largest in France's foreign trade
history.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's dependency rate to the international market has
reached 40 percent. It has official friendship connections with 41
cities in other countries. Two-thirds of all countries with
diplomatic ties to China have consulates in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
With such channels, the city is well-equipped to have a
dialogue with the world.
</P>
<P>
In the past five months, the municipal government has received
more than 50 ministerial trade delegations. Of these delegations,
80 percent had entrepreneurs in their entourage. Statistics also
show that 98 percent of foreign businesses in Shanghai are
successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bank Promises Financing for Telecommunications Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China (BOC) signed an
agreement with the China Unicom today, promising to heavily
finance the second telecommunications giant between 1998 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to a letter of intent the two sides signed today, the
bank will first issue 1.5 billion yuan (180 million US dollars) in
loans to China Unicom to support the company's GSM digital and
mobile telecommunications project in northern Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Other than the financial support in terms of bank loans, bill
acceptance and discounts, and guarantees, the bank is also
expected to act as the financial adviser and conduct settlements
for the company.
</P>
<P>
Most of the financing will go to the China Unicom projects in
GSM digital mobile telecommunications, long-distance
telecommunications and digital telecommunications in provinces
such as Liaoning, Jiangsu, Guangdong and Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
As another indication of the BOC's prior support to large and
profitable enterprises, the bank has signed similar agreements
worth over 23 billion yuan (2.77 billion US dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994, China Unicom is the second Chinese
telecommunications service company ever formed after China
Telecom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
