<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks' Outlook Still Gloomy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares ended higher
Wednesday but off early peaks in a muted reaction to Wall Street's
117 point rise overnight.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 10.2 points up at 2,592.8, all
industrials gained 18.0 points to 4,519.4 and all resources put on
4.1 points to 1,043.3.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said Wednesday's generally touchy trading, despite a
strong performance from U.S. and European markets, reflected the
switch in focus to Asian markets rather than more traditional
indicator markets.
</P>
<P>
"It was a very skittish market which goes to show the
volatility as we switch from the former influences of the northern
hemisphere markets to the Japanese and Hong Kong markets," Peake
Lands Kirwin broker Bill Richmond said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Nikkei index climbed 68.0 points to 15,123.0 over the
day while Hong Kong's Hang Seng index had drifted 32.2 points to
8,187.4.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the mixed Asian performance reinforced the
considerable skepticism about the strength of Wednesday's minor
rally and cited the underperformance of the June Share Price Index
(SPI) contract traded on the Sydney Futures Exchange as evidence.
</P>
<P>
Overall 365.2 million shares changed hands worth 1.126 billion
Australian dollars (686.86 million U.S. dollars) with falling
stocks just shading rising stocks by 583 to 574.
</P>
<P>
The main mover for the day was Foster's Brewing which jumped 26
cents to 3.64 Australian dollars after it announced it had sold
its Canadian brewing interests for 1.11 billion Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. and Telstra installment receipts were boosted thanks
to rumors from the U.S.A. that phone giant AT&AMP;T would launch a 30
billion U.S. dollars takeover bid for cable giant
Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said a takeover of that scale could mean bullish asset
revaluations for all leading telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
Other leading industrials to rise included Lend Lease, up 60
cents, and National Mutual, five cents stronger.
</P>
<P>
The banking index slipped 27.3 points to 5,650.8 with National
slipping 33.1 cents, Commonwealth easing 17.6 cents, Westpac
losing four cents and ANZ up seven cents.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks slipped in line with the 1.90 fall in bullion in
late Sydney trading to 293.60 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
