<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Barely Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A little help from the New
Zealand dollar failed to greatly influence the local currency
Wednesday, leaving the Australian dollar anchored just below 61
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
For the third consecutive day the currency ended the local
session barely changed.
</P>
<P>
While the session was more volatile than the previous two this
week, the currency closed at 60.89 U.S. cents, very near the 60.85
close Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A dip below the crucial 60.50 U.S. cent level early in the
session was not sustained and the bears in the market were
thwarted by the announcement of a better-than-expected current
account deficit figure in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
SBC Warburg Dillon Read foreign exchange executive director
John Radinoff said a subsequent rise in the New Zealand dollar was
accompanied by a lift in the Australian currency which hit 61 U.S.
cents before retreating.
</P>
<P>
Despite the help from its NZ neighbor, a resurgence in the U.S.
dollar against the yen quickly put an end to the rally. Radinoff
said the yen remained the lead factor for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
IBJ Australia senior trader Steve Chater said as long as the
Australian dollar continued to languish at low levels, the bond
market would remain watchful.
</P>
<P>
"The thought of it going below 60 U.S. cents again is going to
drive bonds," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts believe a break of that crucial level would send
the Australian dollar spiraling back down toward its all-time low
of 57.10 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
In the foreign exchange market, the Australian dollar was
buying 85.47 yen from 83.92 previously and 1.0969 German marks
from 1.0908. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
