<HEADLINE> Saudi FM Calls on Iraq to Respect Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has called on
Iraq to honor the U.N. resolution over Iraqi-Kuwaiti border,
principles of the Arab League and the regional security agreements
to show its good will towards its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal made the remarks
at the opening session of the Saudi-Egyptian Higher Committee in
Riyadh Tuesday night, Kuwait News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Faisal's remarks were in response to the recent statement made
by Iraqi Vice President Taha Ramadan regarding Iraqi-Kuwaiti
border.
</P>
<P>
Faisal said Ramadan's statement "is regrettable and indicates
Baghdad's continuous policy of deception."
</P>
<P>
Ramadan was reported to have claimed during his recent visit to
Morocco that the U.N.-demarcated border between Iraq and Kuwait
after the 1991 Gulf War to end Iraq's invasion of Kuwait lacked
"legal ground."
</P>
<P>
The remarks, running against the the U.N. Resolution 833 which
demarcates the boundary between the two countries after the Gulf
War, touched off broad criticism.
</P>
<P>
Terming that Ramadan was misquoted, Iraq has reiterated its
commitment to the resolution 833 after the incident.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Faisal also expressed the hope that Iraq
returns to the Arab and Islamic family, and plays a role on
international affairs. 
</P>
