<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore stock market slid
for a fourth straight day Wednesday as investors awaited the
off-budget measures to be announced next week.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) closed
7.40 points down at 1,074.85 despite the revelation that the
government will announce the much-anticipated package of
off-budget measures in Parliament next Monday to boost the
slowdown economy.
</P>
<P>
The turnover increased to 92.16 million shares worth 188.88
million Singapore dollars (115.88 million U.S. dollars). There
were 141 gainers against 136 losers with 311 stocks unchanged.
</P>
<P>
EasyKnit thk was the most actively traded stock with a volume
of 12.86 million units. DBS Land had 5.85 million shares traded.
Singtel was next with 4.97 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 remained the top gainer of the day, up 1.80
Singapore dollars to 21.30 Singapore dollars. Jurship closed 30
cents up to 8.30 Singapore dollars. UOB F increased by 25 cents to
end at 5.40 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, ANA Ho topped the losers as it fell by 50
cents to finish at 1.50 Singapore dollars. SIA 200 shed 40 cents
to end at 6.40 Singapore dollars. MAA lost 38 cents to close 1.66
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Commentators said that the eager anticipation of the off-budget
measures to boost the economy has given way to the feeling that
the government can do little to turn the situation around.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the off-budget measures, aimed at reducing
business costs and helping companies cope with difficult times,
are not expected to excite the market unless they include some
radical steps.
</P>
<P>
The weakening Japanese yen also cast pall on the local bourse,
they said. 
