<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Asked to Explain for Kaunda's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's former President Kenneth
Kaunda asked current President Frederick Chiluba to explain the
circumstances of his release, the Post newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Kaunda as saying here Tuesday that he has
written a letter to Chiluba asking him to clarify the government
position on his release.
</P>
<P>
"They should not underrate my feelings on this particular
issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he is still waiting for the reply from Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda asserted that he has the duty and moral right to
criticize the government.
</P>
<P>
He said, "If they want advice from me, I
will give it to them and I will respect that. I have a duty to
advise the government without fear or favor."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested on December 25 last year and put under
house arrest six days later on a charge of involvement in the
October 28 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
He was formally charged in February this year with misprision
of treason but freed early this month by Lusaka High Court after
the state entered a nolle prosequi.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda announced four days away from his release that he will
quit party politics so that he can serve the nation and the
continent on a wider scope.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of his resignation is to serve the nation and the
continent on a wide scope and above partisan politics, said
Kaunda, who had been the country's president since its
independence in 1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by current
President Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has been urging Kaunda not to be
involved in party politics but to follow former Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere's example so that he can be respected as
the father of the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
