<HEADLINE> Indonesian President to Appoint New Air Force, Navy, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
will install the new chiefs of staff of the country's Air Force,
Navy and Police next Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Defense Minister and Commander of the
Armed Forces (ABRI) Gen. Wiranto after attending a limited cabinet
meeting on political and security affairs here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president will install Maj. Gen. Hanafie Asnan as Air Force
chief of staff, Vice Admiral Widodo as Navy chief of staff and
Maj. Gen. Roesmanhadi as chief of the State Police, Wiranto said.
</P>
<P>
Asnan presently serves as logistics assistant to the Air Force
chief of staff while Widodo serves as commander of the Navy's
Western Fleet. Roesmanhadi is on Wiranto's staff as expert for
public security and order.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto said the replacement is a normal procedure that is part
of the ABRI's consolidation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Asked on the possibility of replacing the Army chief of staff,
he said Gen. Subagyo is relatively new in his position, compared
to the others.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Habibie asked the people to give ABRI a chance to
conduct "internal consolidation" to enable the Armed Forces to
carry out investigation of cases concerning missing people and
widespread May riots.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told members of the National Commission on Human Rights
that he acknowledged that the credibility of his government
depended heavily on the resolution of the cases.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the internal consolidation meant replacements of
ABRI officials or restructuring, spokesman for the National
Commission for Human Rights Marzuki Darusman only said: "the term
has a wide range of meanings. We just try to understand that."
</P>
</TEXT>
