<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Malawi Fail to Reach Agreement on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 24 (Xinhua) --Discussions were held between the
Mozambican and Malawian presidents, but no agreement was reached
on the privatization of the management of the Nacala railroad and
the Mozambican northern seaport of Nacala.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano made the remarks after
talks with the visiting Malawian President Bakili Muluzi in
Nacala Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The daily Noticias newspaper Wednesday quoted Chissano as
saying that the two sides failed to sign the agreement because
they had different understanding of the target of the
privatization.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president said that the two governments will
hold further talks on the issue.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Malawi hopes that it will hold 16 percent
of the shares of the railroad and port after the management of
the Nacala Corridor is privatized.
</P>
<P>
But President Chissano said that it is too early to make such
estimation.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two governments will hold more talks on new
proposals due to be raised by Malawi. He predicted that an
agreement will be reached eventually.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi expressed his hope that Malawi would not be excluded in
the process of privatizing the management of the corridor.
</P>
<P>
Malawi is the biggest customer of the Nacala Port
and the Nacala Corridor, Muluzi said, therefore it's important to
"let Malawi participate in" the privatization of the management
of the corridor.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian president left Nacala for home Tuesday with the
accompanying Transport and Communications Minister Kamandagabaz
Chambalo, and Agriculture and Irrigation Minister Aleke Banda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
