<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Offshore Oilfield In Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China has developed the Chengdao
Oilfield, off its east coast, with an annual output of 1.05
million tons, making it the largest oilfield in Bohai Bay.
</P>
<P>
According to a China National Petrochemical Corp. (Sinopec)
official, offshore exploration was difficult because of the
complicated geological structure, but engineers at the Shengli
Oilfield developed Chengdao by applying a vast array of new
technology for 3-D seismic surveys and oil reserve studies.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai area has 2.12 million tons of oil output and 367
million cubic meters of gas output annually.
</P>
<P>
Officials expect even greater progress this year in oil and gas
exploration in the Bohai area, and expect 60 million tons of oil
and 10 billion cu.m. of gas reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in Tokyo
Wednesday as Japanese export-oriented high-technology issues were
boosted by the U.S. dollar's upsurge above the 140 yen line.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of Tokyo Stock Exchange gained 68.58 points, or 0.46
percent, from Tuesday's close to finish at 15,123.18.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 5.51 points, or 0.47 percent, to
1,180.93.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section came at an estimated 370 million
shares, down from 421.57 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An overnight rise in New York stocks led by computer and
high-tech issues also supported the Tokyo stock market, but the
renewed weakness of the yen sent bank and real estate shares
falling, traders said.
</P>
<P>
A cheaper yen against the dollar may boost exports of
automobile and high-tech firms, but also discourages foreign
investors from buying Tokyo stocks and other assets, since a weak
yen means less profit on such investments.
</P>
<P>
A weaker yen also puts Asian exporters at more risk, in turn
makes Japanese banks more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, losers edged
gainers 575 to 530, with 154 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
