<HEADLINE> New East China Development Zone For Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- A lubricating oil plant funded by
Royal-Dutch Shell began operation in the Zhapu Development Zone in
China's Zhejiang Province recently.
</P>
<P>
The group also has a pitch factory there. The two projects cost
a total investment of 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Increased overseas investment in Zhapu in recent years shows
that the development zone has become a popular new spot for
overseas investors, says Ruan Xinguang, director of the zone's
management committee.
</P>
<P>
The zone covers 16 sq.km. on the northern edge of Hangzhou Bay,
about 100 km from the leading industrial cities of Shanghai,
Suzhou and Ningbo.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are welcome in the port, real estate,
building materials, petrochemical, machinery, and electronics
sectors, Ruan says.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu has a coastline long enough to build 100 new berths. By
2010, the annual handling capacity of Zhapu Port is expected to
reach 50 million tons.  
</P>
