<HEADLINE> People-to-People Exchanges Boosted as Sino-U.S. Relations Improve (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Hawaii is a household name for the
Chinese, and after President Jiang Zemin's visit to Honolulu last
fall, the people of this island state are showing an growing
interest in China as well.
</P>
<P>
The government of the state of Hawaii and the Chinese Chamber
of Commerce in Honolulu will for the first time jointly launch a
trade mission to China's mainland this fall. Previous trade
mission destinations were confined to Taiwan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The 'China Bonanza' is what everybody is talking about after
President Jiang's visit here, and President Clinton is going to
China, too," said Richard Bahar, an official with Hawaii's
Department of Business, Economic Development and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
Wesley Fong, president of the Chinese Chamber of Commerce in
Honolulu, said that during Jiang's stay in Hawaii he briefed them
on China's economic development and encouraged the Chinese
community in Hawaii to contribute to the growth of the
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"And we're pretty much encouraged," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. relations have been improving constantly and moving
forward in recent years, and President Jiang's visit has pushed
bilateral ties to a higher level, according to Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
Top-level visits and contacts have also boosted
non-governmental cooperation and partnership between the two
countries in economic, trade, cultural, educational and legal
fields, they said.
</P>
<P>
Heartening progress has been made in people-to-people exchanges
and cooperation between the two countries, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Will Not Reschedule Payment of Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Wednesday reiterated that it will not reschedule the payment of
its foreign debts as this will only dampen the trust of the
international community toward the country, a minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Before taking a foreign debt, the government always considers
its capability to repay it," Finance Minister Bambang Subianto
told House Commission VIII on Finance here.
</P>
<P>
Until April, the Indonesian government's foreign debts have
reached 51.7 billion U.S. dollars, including 19.5 billion U.S.
dollars in bilateral debt, 15.5 billion U.S. dollars in
multilateral debt and 13.7 billion U.S. dollars in export credit.
</P>
<P>
All these are soft loans, with low interests and a long term of
payment, and no political commitment, the minister said, adding
that all the loans were used to finance the production sector as
agreed with the creditors.
</P>
<P>
Subianto also explained the progress on the settlement of
private sector foreign debts which reached 78.2 billion U.S.
dollars last February.
</P>
<P>
He cited the agreement reached in Frankfurt, Germany, last June
3 by Indonesian negotiators and representatives of foreign
creditor banks. Under the agreement, Indonesian businessmen will
be given up to eight years to repay their foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
"The government will continue to monitor the settlement of the
country's corporate foreign debts and will issue policies to
control the growth of these debts," Subianto added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People-to-People Exchanges Boosted as Sino-US Relations Improve (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In front of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, hundreds of people
queue up in the morning to apply for visas to the United
States. Some come 4-to-5 hours before the embassy opens.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the 1970s, more than 160,000 Chinese students
and researchers have been to the United States. Of these, more
than 40,000 have returned to China. In 1997 alone, some 3,000
students from the United States have enrolled in Chinese
universities, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. stores are full of commodities with the tag "Made in
China." In China, the blockbuster movie "Titanic" was all the rage
a month ago, and now the streets are flooded with Celine Dion's
passionate singing of "My Heart Will Go On" ... and on, and on.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ice cream store Baskin Robins is a newfound love for
the Chinese with a sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
John Huang, one of the founders of the Beijing branch, said
that China and the United States can be economically and
culturally inter-complementary. Closer bilateral relations are the
common aspiration of the people and in line with historical
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that President Clinton's coming visit to China may
yield new results," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
