<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People-to-People Exchanges Boosted as Sino-U.S. Relations Improve (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The movement of people and commerce between the United States
and China also is on the rise. While buses full of Chinese
tourists shuttle back and forth from Los Angeles in California to
the gambling mecca of Las Vegas in Nevada, container ships from
around the world -- including the United States -- move in and out
of the Tianjin Xingang Foreign Trade Wharf.
</P>
<P>
"According to my observation, our trade with the United States
has been steadily increasing this year," said a Customs
official in the wharf warehouse. The reason is China's economic
stability and its competitiveness, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The improving bilateral ties should also be credited," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese foreign trade officials cited the same reasons for
continuing U.S. investment in China this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent sample survey of 50 American companies,
two-thirds are making money in China, while most of the rest are
not profitable because of long-term investments or managerial
reasons.
</P>
<P>
The people-to-people exchanges between Chinese and Americans
appear to be expanding everywhere. Meetings, talks and
collaborative projects in the areas of law, economy, trade, news
and publication, and religion have been frequently held on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
Nashville, a city in the U.S. state of Tennessee, is best known
as the center of country-western music. But even this city in the
Deep South of the United States will soon have a Chinese judge
from Shanghai. The young magistrate is going to Nashville to learn
how the American court deals with the media. China's newly elected
president of the Supreme People's Court, Xiao Yang, just called
upon the Chinese courts to open to the media for live coverage.
</P>
<P>
"We are excited about the young man's arrival," said Tennessee
Judge Webbe Brothers, adding that "we are also interested in
knowing from him how the Chinese courts work."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
