<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Depressed Tobacco Prices Cause Concern in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco sales that opened on a
depressed note this year have caused concern to all tobacco
growers in central and southern Africa, the Tobacco Association
of Zambia (TAZ) has said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Tuesday, TAZ Executive Director Graham
Wallace said that tobacco prices started off 40 percent below
last year's prices and this shows that the initial pricing fell
below the cost of production for tobacco throughout central and
southern Africa, the weekly Financial Mail reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The trend is now a major concern to all tobacco growers in the
region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wallace said that the tobacco prices in Africa are being
depressed more seriously than in other regions which are in
competition with Africa, like Brazil and North America.
</P>
<P>
The TAZ executive director pointed out that tobacco producers
in Africa now believe that African markets have been unfairly
singled out by buying companies.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this to the quest by these companies to maintain
profit margins in African countries for their overseas
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco growers accept that African markets are being
unfairly singled out by buying companies who want to help them
maintain profit margins in countries for their overseas
shareholders," said Wallace.
</P>
<P>
He added that tobacco growers now accept that there is fairly
widespread nervousness through the manufacturing and marketing
companies as a result of the litigation targeted against the
industry in the United States.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the collapse of the national economies of many
of the Far Eastern countries where much of the tobacco product is
sold has worsened the situation.
</P>
<P>
A grower in Africa is currently receiving less than 1.5 U.S.
Dollars per kilogram for his crop, which is on the same level as
the cost of production. But the same amount of tobacco will sell
overseas for somewhere in the region for 2.8 U.s. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 70 to 80 percent of the value earned from tobacco
sales goes to foreign governments in excise duty and the balance
to shareholders of the manufacturing and merchant companies.
</P>
<P>
Growers in various production companies are coming
increasingly together to share their problems and to press other
parties involved in the industry for a more equitable share of
the benefits, said the TAZ official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
