<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whole Grain Foods May Protect Against Cancers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Diet of whole grain foods,
particularly breads and pasta, may protect against a variety of
cancers, said a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, published on the the latest issue of the
International Journal of Cancer, said that diet with many whole
grain foods may lower the risk of various cancers, including those
affecting the digestive tract (stomach, colon, rectum, liver,
pancreas and gall bladder), and those outside the digestive
system, including cancers of the upper respiratory tract, breast,
prostate, ovary, bladder, and kidney.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Liliane Chatenoud from Milan, Italy, and his colleagues,
who conducted this survey in northern Italy, had studied more than
10,000 hospital patients with a variety of cancers and almost
8,000 patients treated for non-cancerous conditions from 1983 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
They speculated that whole grains may have antioxidant effects,
reducing the risk of cancer by "mopping up" cancer-causing free
radical molecules formed during some cells processes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Registers Trade Surplus in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea registered a trade
surplus of 3.73 billion U.S. dollars last month on the basis of
customs clearance, said the Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the nation's exports stood at 11.39 billion dollars
while its imports were 7.66 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though exports fell three percent last month compared with the
same time of 1997, the balance recorded a surplus.
</P>
<P>
The continued reduction in facility investment since January
this year did make the sharp reduction in import.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the decreased exports to the
depreciation of the currencies in Southeast Asian countries and
the inability to obtain export financing at home.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, South Korean exports
amounted to 55.87 billion dollars, up 5.7 percent over the same
time of 1997, while imports totaled 39.79 billion dollars, down
35.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the trade surplus at that period came to 16.07 billion
dollars, accounting for 64.4 percent of the government's targeted
trade surplus of 25 billion dollars for 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
