<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Businesses Active in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- American businesses, attracted by
the favorable overseas investment atmosphere in Shanghai, are
playing a role in the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, the 2,293 businesses with U.S. backing there
had 3.3 billion U.S. dollars worth of committed foreign
investment, or 11 percent of Shanghai's total.
</P>
<P>
American business involvement in Shanghai goes back to 1982,
and because of good returns by pioneering U.S. companies, by 1995,
more than 350 U.S. companies were opening businesses in Shanghai,
at the rate of about one a day.
</P>
<P>
U.S.-funded businesses are having a profound influence on
Shanghai's industrial structure, according to industrial
analysts. Shanghai General Motors - the biggest U.S.-funded
company in Shanghai - was established last year and the first
Buick-Shanghai sedan is scheduled to come off the assembly line at
the end of this year. The company's annual production is targeted
at 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Other leading U.S. manufacturers in Shanghai are
McDonnell-Douglas, 3M, Westinghouse, and Hewlett-Packard. American
businesses are also involved in Shanghai's thriving service
industry. McDonald's and Kentucky Fried Chicken have more than 100
outlets, and Citibank has moved its Asian headquarters from Hong
Kong to Shanghai and become one of first banks doing business in
renminbi, the Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Secretariat Working on Agenda of 10th Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Secretariat of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) is in close
touch with the host nation and other member countries of the
grouping to finalize the agenda and other preparations for the
10th SAARC summit.
</P>
<P>
A number of important activities have taken place in recent
months including five ministerial meetings on commerce, tourism,
environment, information and communications, and the outcome of
these will be considered by the forthcoming summit scheduled for
July 29-31 in Colombo, Sri Lanka, the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat said in a press release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, economic issues, in particular those of strengthening
the SAARC Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA) and
establishing a South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA), are expected
to figure prominently at the summit, the secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of trade negotiations have been concluded under
SAPTA launched in December 1995, offering more than 2,000 items of
products for tariff cuts ranging from 10 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also study the report of the Group of Eminent
Persons which was commissioned by the 9th SAARC summit in May 1997
to undertake a comprehensive review of the functioning of SAARC
and to prepare a plan of action for the new millennium, it said.
</P>
<P>
The group met four times between December 1997 and early June
this year, and made an extensive appraisal of the progress of
SAARC since its establishment in December 1985.
</P>
<P>
The group had made a number of recommendations for
strengthening the institutional setup of the regional grouping and
developing a long-range vision for the future, the secretariat
said.
</P>
<P>
Kanti Kumar Poddar, president of the SAARC Chamber of Commerce
and Industry, told the press here Monday that he head learned the
group had recommended the postponement from 2001 to 2008 of the
realization of SAFTA.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the recommendation, saying that it is against the
will of the South Asian business community. He was in Nepal to
lobby for the idea of a SAARC Economic Union by the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
Several meetings of SAARC countries will take place in Colombo
before the summit, the secretariat said.
</P>
<P>
The 20th session of the Council of Ministers is slated for July
27-28, while the Standing Committee comprising the foreign
secretaries of the member countries will convene on July 25-26, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian Food Security Reserve Board will also meet
during the course of the meetings preceding the summit. The South
Asian Food Security Reserve, operational since August 1988, serves
as a cushion against food shortages in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, presentation of the SAARC Youth Award 1998 will take
place when the Council of Ministers meets, the secretariat added.
</P>
<P>
The award was established last year to encourage the youth in
the region in participatory work and innovative activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Joint Arab Actions on Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has called for Arabs' common
strategy and joint actions in handling the Arab-Israel issues,
especially the Palestine issue.
</P>
<P>
The call was made during a joint meeting of Iraq's Revolution
Command Council and Regional Command of Arab Socialist Baath
Party, which was held on Tuesday night under the chairmanship of
President Saddam Hussein, the Iraqi News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership believed that all Arab forces should be
mobilized to back up Arab nation's common strategy, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
The call was made when Arab countries are planning a summit on
the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The peace negotiations between Palestinians and Israel have
been stalled since March last year due to Israeli government's
hardline policy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also called on Arab countries to help lift U.N.
sanctions off Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting also discussed Iraq's relationship with the
U.N. Security Council and Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
disarmament in Iraq, saying that Iraq's open letter on May 1 this
year to the Security Council should be the basis for settling all
problems.
</P>
<P>
In that letter, the Iraqi leadership demanded the lifting of
trade embargo imposed on Iraq as a prelude to the overall lifting
of U.N. economic sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting also criticized the United States and UNSCOM
for trying to prolong the sanctions on Iraqi people, said the
agency report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
