<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Economic Future Looks Promising: Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's economic future looks
promising because the Zimbabwean government has taken some
significant steps to resolve some of the major problems facing
the country's economy, noted an official from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the Zimbabwe-Britain Society in
Harare Tuesday night, the World Bank President's Representative
in Zimbabwe, David Cook, said that the Zimbabwean government has
taken significant steps on the fisc through the reduction of its
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The government of Zimbabwe has also made progress in
rebuilding its foreign exchange reserves, which had been depleted
by the crash of the Zimbabwean Dollar last November.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's economic outlook is "so far good," Cook was quoted
by the daily Herald as reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The economic fundamentals of Zimbabwe are really not that
bad. They are manageable," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the fisc side, Cook said that the latest indications are
that the government is on course to meet the set target of
reducing its expenditure to reasonable levels.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government is expected to reduce the budget
deficit to 7.5 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) during
this financial year.
</P>
<P>
Investor confidence is slowly picking up after suffering a
setback during the last half of last year over uncertainty
regarding funding of war veterans and the government's policy on
the land reform program, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that more still needs to be done on the
banking sector where confidence has been low after the collapse
of the United Merchant Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
