<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Largest Borrower from World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 24 (Xinhua) -- China continued to be the largest
borrower of investment loans from the World Bank in fiscal year
1998 which ended on June 30, receiving 2.6 billion U.S. dollars,
or 9 percent of the World Bank's overall commitments.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Resident Mission in China of the World Bank
said that China has used these loans to finance 16 development
projects.
</P>
<P>
China rejoined the World Bank in 1981 and became its largest
borrower in fiscal year 1993. By the end of fiscal year 1998,
World Bank loans to China had grown to about 30.359 billion
U.S. dollars to finance 200 projects.
</P>
<P>
Lending for transportation, energy, industrial, urban
development and other infrastructure projects accounted for more
than half of the total portfolio, with the remainder going to
agriculture, social sectors, environment and water supply and
sanitation, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
World Bank sources said the bank's mandate in China is to
support broad-based economic development in the pursuit of poverty
reduction. Projects aided by the bank have played a unique role in
supporting China's economic reform and modernization process,
targeting the alleviation of poverty, infrastructure development
and human resources development.
</P>
<P>
"In the midst of the Asian crisis, it is encouraging to note
that China's overall economic performance remains strong and that
the bank's portfolio of projects continues to be one of the best
in the bank," said Yukon Huang, Director of the World Bank China
Program. "This provides a good basis for the bank to assist China
in coping with the challenges that lie ahead." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
