<HEADLINE> Iraq Denies U.S. Allegation of Having Nerve Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has categorically denied the
U.S. allegation that it has nerve gas warheads, the Iraqi News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted an Iraqi National Monitoring Department
spokesman as saying Tuesday night that the U.S. allegation is the
same kind of rumors as those fabricated before by the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on disarmament in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Army laboratory in Aberdeen, Maryland, has reportedly
claimed to find traces of the deadly VX nerve gas on Iraq's
missile warheads.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that it was surprising that UNSCOM
chose a U.S. army laboratory to make experiments and draw
conclusion, rather than choosing laboratories from neutral
countries.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler will brief the Security Council
Thursday on his talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz
10 days ago in Baghdad, during which the two sides reached an
agreement on the program of work for the next two months.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said in a letter to the Security Council recently that
Iraqi scientists had experimented with VX but were unable to turn
it into a weapon, and that 1.7 tonnes of the agent had been
produced but it was not of weapons grade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
