<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Kenyan Banks Reduce Base Lending Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Four leading banks in Kenya have
decided to lower their base rates on loans after the government
presented the 1998/99 budget aimed at narrowing budget deficit at
the parliament two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Commercial Bank announced Tuesday it will reduce its
base lending rate from 27.5 percent to 26.5 percent from July 1,
following similar moves by Barclays Bank, Standard Chartered Bank
and ABN-Amro Bank.
</P>
<P>
The down also came after a general decline in Treasury Bill
yields as the government cuts its borrowing from the public.
</P>
<P>
Maurice Kanga, chief economist of the Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK), said Tuesday that the average interest on the 91-Treasury
Bill declined to 25.40 percent in the auction dated June 2,
compared to 25.42 in the previous auction.
</P>
<P>
Kanga said that liquidity in the domestic market tightened
during the week to June 19, with the average interbank borrowing
rate moving from 15.26 percent on June 15 to 26.82 percent on
June 19, due to tax payments.
</P>
<P>
"The Central Bank of Kenya has since injected liquidity
through the Repurchase Agreements (Repos) with banks to ease the
situation," Kanga said in the weekly CBK bulletin.
</P>
<P>
On exchange rates, CBK said the Shilling went on strengthening
against the hard currencies, with an average exchange rate of
59.72 Shillings to the U.S. Dollar and 99.44 to the Pound,
compared to 60.98 Shillings and 99.65 Shillings to the Dollar and
the Pound respectively in the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
