<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Chinese Run Greater Risk of Osteoporosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Elderly Chinese are running a
greater risk of suffering the bone disease osteoporosis and
related fractures, according to research in one of China's largest
city.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of fractures among Shanghai residents aged 60 and
older almost doubled in the 1990-1997 period, rising to 9.96
percent from 3.35 percent in males and 15.28 percent from 8.78
percent in females.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Shanghai Institute of Gerontology told the
"Wenhui Daily" that rapid aging of the Chinese population,
improper diet and lack of physical exercise have led to more
osteoporosis cases.
</P>
<P>
And Shanghai is not alone. Experts in Beijing warned that China
has had about 84 million osteoporosis sufferers, about 76 percent
of the population 60 and older.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of a greying wave in China, the number of patients
will increase to 110 million by 2010, and exceed 200 million by
the middle of the next century, said Professor Liu Zhonghou,
chairman of the Osteoporosis Committee of the China Gerontological
Society.
</P>
<P>
Female osteoporosis patients outnumber males 6-to-1 in China,
and as they get older their bones are more susceptible to
fractures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, many people still underestimate the danger of
the disease and pay little attention to prevention, he said.
</P>
<P>
World Osteoporosis Day was launched last year on June 24 to
increase people's awareness of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Experts have suggested that old people eat more calcium-rich
food, get some sunshine, and do proper physical exercises to
prevent the disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
