<HEADLINE> U.N. Trains African Army on Logistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations began training
African military personnel on logistics so as to help Africa to
response skillfully to the rising need for peacekeeping
operations in the continent.
</P>
<P>
A 10-day U.N.-sponsored logistics course, opened by Kenya's
Chief of General Staff General, Daudi Tonje, Tuesday in Nairobi,
is attended by service commanders and senior military officers
from different African countries, local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the course is to support the build-up of U.N.
logistics knowledge, an area that has been identified by African
member states as weak, said Tonje in a speech.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya and most African member states have in the past been
involved in peacekeeping missions and have responded to crises in
several parts of the world whenever called upon," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our armies must be organized, equipped, and trained to
adequately manage our basic function of defending our countries
with minimal resources," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The deputy military advisor to U.N. boss Kofi Annan, Mohinder
Bhagat, said the course is modeled on the U.N. training conducted
by Canada and Norway.
</P>
<P>
"Logistics is the key element in assuring the timely,
successful and effective deployment of a U.N. peacekeeping
operation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Too often, U.N operations have been constrained by the
support that has been provided and it is only through the
preparation of member states staff that we will overcome these
limitations," he said.
</P>
<P>
The course will end on July 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
