<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder for President Clinton's China Trip: Cleaning Up River To Beautify South China Tourist Attraction-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Gao Quanzhong, whose family has
live alongside the Lijiang river in south China city for
generations, is a member of a special team of 94 farmers who are
protecting the woods along the river, which is a major tourist
attraction for the city of Guilin.
</P>
<P>
But, its thriving tourism and industry had caused environmental
problems, so Guilin started to close heavily polluting factories
back in 1979, and has so far shut down 49 in spite of losses to
the local economy.
</P>
<P>
It has also built four sewage disposal plants that treat 40
percent of the city's waste water, and ten garbage-disposal sites
to treat 81 percent of the city's garbage. And, boats using the
Lijiang have been equipped with waste storage facilities to
prevent the direct discharge of human waste into the river. More
trees have also been planted along the river. "With the river
getting cleaner, many fish have come back," said the 50-year-old
Gao.
</P>
<P>
The return of the fish is one of the more remarkable changes
that have come to one of China's most beautiful rivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
