<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Enjoys Popular Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The just-concluded poll, conducted among 36,190 people by the
Suan Dusit Rajabhat Institute, showed that 61.98 percent of the
respondents were satisfied with Chuan's performance so far, while
48.91 percent were happy with the work of his six-party coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll findings available Wednesday, 42.68
percent were satisfied with the government efforts to tackle
national problems; 42.98 percent were happy with the coalition's
unity; 45.98 percent with its clean image; and 48.48 percent with
its non-interference in state agency affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan government also scored 6.78 points out of 10 for its
performance over the six months in office.
</P>
<P>
The Chuan government's score was higher than the 5.01 points
for the previous Chavalit Yongchaiyudh administration, and 5.05
for the 1995-96 government of Banharn Silpa-archa in the same
period of time after coming into office.
</P>
<P>
The poll revealed that the Chuan government was popular in all
regions of the country except the impoverished northeast which
preferred Chavalit of the New Aspiration Party.
</P>
<P>
Pollster Sukhum Chalooeysap said Chuan's popularity was a major
factor contributing to the stability of his coalition government.
</P>
<P>
On the question of which areas of government performance they
found to be least satisfactory, 47.05 percent pointed to the
rising cost of living, 12.19 percent to growing unemployment and
10.37 percent to traffic problems in big cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
