<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Scientists Discover Test for EPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian sport scientists
claimed a major breakthrough on Wednesday in the battle against
doping with the discovery of the first test to detect the banned
substance erythropoietin (EPO).
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Sydney, the director of the
internationally acclaimed Australian Institute of Sport (AIS), Dr
Ross Smith, said the institute had developed a screening test it
hoped could be approved for the Sydney 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
EPO stimulates the production of red blood cells around the
body and is believed to be widely used in endurance sports such as
cycling and cross-country skiing. But it has also been linked to
the deaths of several athletes.
</P>
<P>
Smith said: "We know that EPO dramatically changes the
parameters of the blood cells and we believe we have found a
screening method that can detect those changes."
</P>
<P>
EPO was first introduced in the mid-1980s to treat kidney
disease, but is now considered one of the most dangerous drugs in
sport.
</P>
<P>
Smith said AIS scientists had discovered that artificial EPO
altered the profile of red blood cells which behaved differently
when they came into contact with haemoglobin or iron.
</P>
<P>
Natalie Howson, chief executive of the Australian Sports Drug
Agency, said the development of a foolproof test would be a major
breakthrough in the fight against drugs in sport.
</P>
<P>
Smith said a series of controlled tests would be carried out on
24 high-level athletes over the next two months.
</P>
<P>
He said the results would be presented to the IOC, which would
ultimately decide whether or not to introduce blood testing in
time for the Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sees Surging Public Sector Borrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' public sector
borrowing requirement is expected to double to 83.8 billion pesos
(2.09 billion U.S. dollars) this year from the original projection
due to increased borrowings of the government.
</P>
<P>
The original public sector borrowing target was 43.2 billion
pesos (1.1 billion dollars), which was already higher than the
40.3 billion pesos (1 billion dollars) posted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The increased borrowing of the government and other government
agencies was due to the sharp drop in revenue collection,
officials of the central bank told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With less revenues, the government will have to source some of
its funding through borrowings from the private sector, they said.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in revenue collection has been attributed to the
economic slowdown caused by the regional currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The public sector borrowing requirement is the aggregate
borrowings of the national government, local government units,
government-owned corporations, government financial institutions,
the central bank and government-run social security systems.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the country's four economic performance criteria
monitored by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The deterioration in the fiscal position of the national
government also caused public sector borrowing to balloon.
</P>
<P>
The national government is projected to post a budget deficit
of 36.8 billion pesos (920 million dollars) this year instead of
an earlier-expected 5 billion peso (125 million dollars) surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
