<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Begin Industrial Park Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on six
large-scale industrial projects will begin soon at Sri Lanka's
industrial park at Sitavaka 40 kilometers west of the capital city
of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Development Minister C. V. Gooneratne Tuesday handed
over the letters of approval to the six pioneers of the Sitavaka
industrial park, Industrial Development Ministry sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These projects will employ more than 3,000 people, they said.
</P>
<P>
A further 10 projects would be given approval in two weeks and
several applications for joint ventures with foreign technical and
financial collaboration had also been received, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
These applications involve investors from India, Sweden,
Britain, Malaysia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
They said the industrial park will have ventures for the
manufacture of wooden products, rubber goods, high value garments,
soft toys, embroidery, zip fasteners, gems and jewelry, industrial
safety equipment and mineral products, and food processing.
</P>
<P>
The products will be mainly for export. Special incentives
including a 10-year tax holiday are offered to the investors.
</P>
<P>
The industrial park is located on a 168-hectare area at
Sitavaka and is the largest infrastructural project in the
country. The construction started in July 1997 and will be
completed this December.
</P>
<P>
The project, funded by the Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund
of Japan and the Consolidated Fund of Sri Lanka, is estimated to
cost 3.6 billion rupees (about 61.91 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
