<HEADLINE> More Chinese Muslims Making Pilgrimages to Mecca (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1984, Du spent 8,000 yuan (975 U.S. dollars) on his first
pilgrimage to Mecca.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the government's policy on privately run
enterprises, Du's eldest son ran a factory in the neighboring
Inner Mongolian Autonomous Region. A second son has a fur and
cashmere business, and a third son runs an Islamic restaurant in
Wuqing City.
</P>
<P>
Having earned more money, Du made his second pilgrimage to
Mecca in 1994, accompanied by his eldest son and daughter-in-law.
This time, the cost of the trip for each of his family members was
21,400 yuan (2,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ningxia and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region are the
country's area's inhabited by the most Moslems. The annual per
capita income of rural residents in the two regions in 1997 was at
least 14 times higher than 20 years before.
</P>
<P>
Ma Zhengang, a 52-year-old farmer in Guyuan Prefecture, said
improved transportation has made it easier for Muslims to go on
Mecca trips. He recalled that it took his father-in-law three
years to cover the whole pilgrimage when he traveled by camel and
sought temporary jobs during the journey.
</P>
<P>
Now, highways link all the counties in the region's mountainous
areas. He said Muslims now take trains to Beijing and fly
chartered planes to Saudi Arabia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Muslims Making Pilgrimages to Mecca (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Wang Jinyu, 24, has finally
realized his dream to make a "Haji", or pilgrimage, to Mecca in
Saudi Arabia, the sixth member in his family.
</P>
<P>
The grandson-in-law of 88-year-old Imam Du Wanzhen in northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, Wang is among 50,000
wealthy Chinese Muslims who have made pilgrimages to Mecca since
1985.
</P>
<P>
Xue Shenglin, deputy head of the Islamic Association of China,
said 5,000 Chinese Muslims made pilgrimages to Mecca this year and
half of them went in groups organized by the association.
</P>
<P>
At least one of every 400 Muslims among China's 20 million
Muslims has made a pilgrimage to Mecca, he said. Making the
pilgrimage is considered one of the five most important things in
the lifetime of a Muslim.
</P>
<P>
Du has been the Imam, or officiating priest at his mosque, for
half a century. He made his first pilgrimage to Mecca in 1984 when
he was in his 70s.
</P>
<P>
However, in the following 14 years, five more of his family
members went on pilgrimages to Mecca because of the family's
improved living standard.
</P>
<P>
Xue said the government guarantees normal religious activities
and those who can afford to go are being allowed to go on
pilgrimages.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1989, the association sent Muslims to Mecca on
chartered planes together with translators and doctors.
</P>
<P>
Du said that since China's implementation in the 1970s of a new
policy on the use of agricultural land, his family leased half a
hectare to grow vegetables, which are sold in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
