<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Leaves for Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina left here Wednesday morning for a one-day official visit to
Pakistan to discuss the situation in South Asia following the
nuclear tests by India and Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who made a similar day-long visit to India
earlier this month, is scheduled to return home in the evening.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to discuss the situation that has arisen out of
the nuclear tests (by India and Pakistan last month). We will give
our views and hear theirs," Foreign Secretary Mostafizur Rahman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister would discuss with her Pakistani counterpart
Nawaz Sharif bilateral, regional and international issues, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina is the first head of government to visit her country's
two South Asian neighbors, after India exploded five nuclear
devices on May 11 and 13, and Pakistan retaliated by six tests on
May 28 and 30.
</P>
<P>
"We want peace and stability in the region. Arms race will not
benefit anyone," Hasina said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister ruled out her role as a mediator
between India and Pakistan. "I am not mediating and I will not do
so," she said.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Hasina sent separate letters to Sharif and
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, expressing her
willingness to visit the two countries to discuss the situation
after the tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
