<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Joint-venture Automakers in Vietnam Stop Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Two joint-venture car assemblies,
Ford-Vietnam and Nissan-Vietnam, have stopped their operations,
reports here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Ford-Vietnam, located near Hanoi, came to a stop after six
months' operations because of its inability to sell its products
in the Vietnamese market, which was saturated with imported cars.
</P>
<P>
Nissan-Vietnam, which was situated in Da Nang City in central
Vietnam, cancelled its assembly line construction due to capital
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
There are 14 joint-venture car assemblies in Vietnam with an
estimated total design capacity of 140,000 units a year or 30
percent higher than the figure predicted for Vietnam's market by
2010.
</P>
<P>
However, only eight of the 14 joint-ventures are currently in
operation and they are unable to run at full capacity at this initial
stage.
</P>
<P>
Official reports showed that automakers in Vietnam sold only
5,700 units in domestic market last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
