<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Rates Rise in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 24 (Xinhua) -- About one million Cambodians
soon could be infected with the AIDS virus if tougher preventive
measures are not taken, the Cambodia Daily Wednesday quoted
Minister of Health Chhea Thaing as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chhea Thaing made the warning at a meeting of the National
Committee for HIV/AIDS and STD Prevention and Control Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that although condom sales has increased to 900,000
pieces a month, the AIDS problem is still growing. Data from the
Health Ministry showed there are between 30 and 50 new infections
a day. Cases of HIV are concentrated heavily among the 5 million
people living in Phnom Penh and the surrounding provinces.
</P>
<P>
Chhea Thaing also warned the increasing number in housewives
falling into the victims to the virus. In Cambodia, AIDS is no longer
a monoply for sexually active people. About 20,000 housewives have
contracted HIV from their husbands. A further 40,000 are at the risk
from infected husbands. An estimated 120,000 Cambodians are
HIV-positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
