<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Vetos Bill on Sanctions Against Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday vetoed legislation that imposes sanctions on foreign
governments or businesses supplying ballistic missile technology
to Iran, saying it would damage the national interest.
</P>
<P>
"This bill would hinder, not help, our overall national
interests ... making it harder to achieve the goals it is
intended to serve," Clinton said in a written statement.
"Therefore, I am vetoing this bill."
</P>
<P>
The veto of the Iran Missile Proliferation Act came at a time
when Clinton expressed his hope last week for a "genuine
reconciliation with Iran" if it complies with the so-called standards
the United States set up as conditions for normalization of relations.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has already eased travel to the
United States for Iranians and is supporting cultural and
academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
As a gesture of rapprochement with Iran, Clinton decided last
month to waive sanctions against French, Russian and Malaysian
firms that have reached a deal with Iran for investment in its
energy sector.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said earlier that sanctions
legislation produced "hopeless shackles on the presidency,"
leaving no flexibility for the president on foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, McCurry said, the legislation cast such a wide
net that some companies or countries would be unfairly punished,
possibly backfiring on U.S. goals of halting missile technology
transfers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said he was particularly concerned about the
bill's impact on the U.S. effort to work with Russia to stem the
flow of technology from Russia to Iran's missile program.
</P>
<P>
But the legislation failed to take into account the progress
that the administration had made in persuading Russia not to sell
missile technology to Iran, he said.
</P>
<P>
The administration is appearing to rethink its sanctions policy
as the United States has been facing strong opposition from allies
who condemned U.S. sanctions that punished foreign firms doing
business with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Some members of Congress have threatened to override the veto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
