<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BankAmerica Expects U.S. Trade Deficit to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The overall U.S. trade deficit
will go up to 145 billion U.S. dollars this year, from 114 billion
dollars in 1997, according to the Bank of America's latest forecast.
</P>
<P>
Two economists of the bank said they made the forecast, which
was outlined in the bank's June Economic &AMP; Business Outlook,
mainly in consideration of the impact of Asia's economic crisis
and the continued domestic economic growth of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. merchandise trade deficit has been widening since the
economy emerged from recession in 1991, and will further rise in
1998 as a result of robust U.S. economic growth and past dollar
strength, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank predicted that the U.S. merchandise trade deficit will
reach 232 billion dollars in 1998, up from 199 billion dollars in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall could be larger if U.S. consumer spending remains
stronger than currently anticipated, said the bank.
</P>
<P>
By contrast, the services component of U.S. trade is growing
rapidly, producing a record surplus of 85 billion dollars in 1997,
and is expected to grow further this year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exports to Asia, excluding Japan, were down 15.9 percent
in March from a year earlier. Domestically, continued strength in
the consumer and business sector will keep U.S. import flows
running strong, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Reinforcing these trends is the recent strengthening in the
trade-weighted exchange value of the U.S. dollar, which makes
U.S. exports less competitive while cheapening U.S. imports, the
bank economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
