<HEADLINE> Tropical Fish Moving to Mediterranean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of tropical fish
species, attracted by the increasingly warm waters of the
Mediterranean, are making the sea their permanent home and
threatening its ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
A study by Icram, Italy's leading marine research center, said
there were 55 species of warm-water fish in the Mediterranean,
making up 20 percent of its fish life. In 1986, there were only
40 species there.
</P>
<P>
This increase is attributed to the rising water temperature of
the Mediterranean, which has risen one degree in the past 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The warm-water fish, coming from the Saharan Atlantic and the
Red Sea, have thrived in part because indigenous Mediterranean
species have been weakened by over-fishing and deteriorating
environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
The red mullet, a newcomer in the sea, has become a major
economic resource along the Egyptian coast. The siganus is
replacing the salpa in the eastern Mediterranean. The globefish
is now common in Sicily and the striped sea urchin, an Atlantic
fish, also comes to Sicily.
</P>
<P>
Italian Environment Minister Edo Ronchi described the changes
in the distribution of species Tuesday as a worrying indication of
climatic change. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
