<HEADLINE> Italian Lower House Approves NATO Expansion Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy's lower house approved NATO's
eastwards expansion Tuesday in what had become a vital test for
Premier Romano Prodi's center-left government.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved by 310 votes in favor, with 79 against
and 169 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Olive Tree coalition, along with the small
opposition Democratic Union for the Republic party, voted for the
bill, which allows NATO to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic as its new members.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation Party and the Northern League voted
against while the Freedom Front abstained.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting, Prodi appealed to all parties to vote in
favor of the bill to ratify NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that the outcome of the vote would in no way
affect his government, which would continue to work on the program
it presented to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
He said: "What is at stake is the ability of our parliament and
our nation to demonstrate to its allies and to the whole world
that Italy is well aware of its responsibilities, its duties and
its international interests well beyond any coalition which
governs at the time."
</P>
<P>
The premier said that the Atlantic alliance had performed, and
still did, the role of guaranteeing security to member nations in
the most efficient and long-lasting way. 
</P>
