<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PAL Creditors Barred From Pressing Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) and a U.S. bankruptcy court have barred
banks, suppliers, leasers and other parties from pressing their
claims against the cash-strapped Philippine Airlines (PAL), a
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
PAL legal counsel Estelito Mendoza was quoted by the Manila
Times as saying Tuesday that a U.S. bankruptcy court has issued a
temporary restraining order barring all persons or entities
anywhere in the U.S. from pursuing or enforcing claims against
PAL.
</P>
<P>
The order was issued by the bankruptcy court in the northern
district of California in response to PAL's petition against
American firm Aviation Sales Leasing Co., one of PAL's aircraft
leasers, which had filed for claims against the airline.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, the SEC also issued an order suspending all claims
pending before any local court or body against the debt-ridden and
strike-crippled national flag carrier.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. bankruptcy court's order, which effectively restrains
PAL's US-based creditors from seizing any of the airline's assets,
will be effective until July 2.
</P>
<P>
Mendoza said if PAL encounters a similar problem with its
creditors in Europe, the company will also seek the same
protection.
</P>
<P>
The SEC on Tuesday created a receivership committee to take
custody of all existing assets and properties of PAL and discuss a
rehabilitation program filed by the company last Friday.
</P>
<P>
PAL said in the petition that it was unable to pay a total of
2.1 billion dollars in debt due to its deteriorating financial
situation aggravated by the ongoing strike of its pilots.
</P>
<P>
The airline said it plans to retrench some 5,000 employees or
40 percent of its workforce, suspend more than two-thirds of
routes and dispose of dozens of airplanes.
</P>
<P>
SEC Chairman Perfecto Yasay said the interim receiver will
assist PAL and SEC in drafting a rehabilitation plan that will
save the company from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, no concrete agreements were reached in a
meeting between PAL officials and officers of the PAL Employees
Association which has filed a notice of strike protesting the
airline's retrenchment program.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the striking PAL pilots' union showed no signs of
conciliation with the management. The devastating strike of some
600 PAL pilots, which entered the 21st day Wednesday, has cost PAL
more than 2 billion pesos (50 million dollars) in lost revenue,
PAL said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
