This means that the plant has paid off the first package of
overseas loans due to its successful operation and efficient use
of funds, experts said.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has paid off 2.6 billion U.S. dollars in
construction loans and 700 million of circulating loans credited
by the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that paying off such a big loan package has earned
a reputation for both the bank and the plant, which is China's
first nuclear power plant built with foreign investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Urged to Be Stricter Against Bank Failures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
needs to enhance its ability to enforce regulations to contain the
rise in bank failures, a U.S.-based international credit rating
agency says.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Wednesday, Moody's Investors Services
said the central bank's inability to conduct surprise examinations
and the problem of corruption among bank examiners had weakened
the bank's capacity to effectively implement banking regulations.
</P>
<P>
"The monitoring and supervisory power of the central bank is
significantly constrained by its inability to conduct surprise
examinations," Moody's said in the report on the outlook of the
Philippine banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Special examinations need to be approved by the Monetary Board
but Moody's said that after the board's clearance is obtained, "it
has already long lost the element of surprise."
</P>
<P>
Moody's also raised the issue of corruption of bank examiners,
the first time the matter was mentioned in an analysis of the
problems confronting the country's banking sector.
</P>
<P>
"The widespread corruption of bank examiners, which often is
responsible for failure in early detection, further weakens the
regulatory powers of the central bank," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Quite often, the central bank comes into a troubled bank to
clean up the mess, instead of performing its preventive duties."
</P>
<P>
Moody's also outlined broad policy recommendations towards
containing the adverse impact of the region-wide crisis on the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
One of these is for the incoming administration to continue the
market-oriented reform agenda of the Ramos government. Another is
the need for more effective enforcement of existing banking
regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
