<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Exchange Reserves Decline Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia's net international
reserves declined further, but continued to meet the International
Monetary Fund (IMF)'s performance criteria, a local newspaper
report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a statement issued by Bank Indonesia Tuesday
as saying that the country's net international reserves declined
by 65.8 million U.S. dollars to 14.601 billion dollars on June 19
from 14.667 billion dollars on June 12 due to overseas debt
payment and the depreciation of the Japanese yen against the U.S.
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The level of 14.601 billion dollars was still higher than the
minimum level of 13.18 billion dollars agreed at the end of March
with the IMF, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia, the central bank, also said that the subsidized
credit facility to finance the procurement of essential food
commodities rose by 313 billion rupiah (31.25 million dollars) to
19.63 trillion rupiah (about 1.96 billion dollars) on June 19
compared to 19.31 trillion rupiah (1.93 billion dollars) on June
12.
</P>
<P>
Liquidity injection for troubled banks under the Indonesian
Banks Restructuring Agency rose to 133.28 trillion rupiah (about
13.3 billion dollars) from 131.91 trillion rupiah (13.17 billion
dollars), the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also reported that money in circulation rose
by 193 billion rupiah (19.27 million dollars) to 67.37 trillion
rupiah (about 6.7 billion dollars), but was still below the
maximum level allowed by the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
