<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossil Animals Boost Dinosaur-Bird Connection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Two fossil animals found in
China have helped substantiate the theory that birds evolved directly
from small, carnivorous, ground-dwelling dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from China, Canada and the United States announced
their findings at a joint press conference held at the National
Geographic Association in Washington Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The feathered animals, whose bodies have many dinosaur
features, were discovered in the rich fossil beds of China's
Liaoning Province in 1996-98. More than 120 million years old,
they support the thinking of most paleontologists that birds
evolved from a dinosaur group known as theropods.
</P>
<P>
"They make the relationship between dinosaurs and birds closer
and closer, but they also make the definition and concept of birds
more and more indistinct," said Ji Qiang, director of China's
National Geological Museum.
</P>
<P>
Replicas of the animals, named Protarchaeopteryx robusta and
Caudipteryx zoui, will be on display to the public from June 24 to
July 26.
</P>
<P>
The link between dinosaurs and birds was first noted by
naturalist Thomas Henry Huxley in the mid-1800s. Most scientists
support the theory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Makes Huge Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Motorola, one of the world's
leading mobile phone makers, has decided to invest an additional
1.5 billion U.S. dollars in Tianjin over the upcoming two and half
years to expand production, a company executive announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to expand production of the most
sophisticated semiconductor integrated circuit chips used in
automotive electronic components, energy products and other
telecommunications components.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after China allowed foreign-funded
projects to be exempted from tariffs and import-related
value-added taxes on equipment imported for their own use, said
P. Y. Lai, president of Motorola China Electronics Ltd.
</P>
<P>
This government policy affects 186 project which fall in 18
categories in the fields of industry, agriculture, forestry,
animal husbandry and fishery.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Motorola will put to use in September a Motorola
Iridium mobile telecommunications global network at a cost of 270
million U.S. dollars. The system includes 66 communications
satellites, which have already been positioned.
</P>
<P>
It will also invest 50-to-100 million U.S. dollars to build a
training center for Chinese management personnel.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of these projects, the total investment of
Motorola in China is expected to reach 2.5 billion U.S. dollars by
2000.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin, the largest coastal city in north China, is the
principal production base of Motorola in China and Asia. The
company invested 720 million U.S. dollars to build a semiconductor
chip factory in Tianjin in November of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The company's sales in China soared to 3.1 billion U.S. dollars
in 1996, accounting for 11 percent of its global sales. It is now
the largest U.S. investor and the second largest foreign-funded
firm in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
