<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation May Exceed 80 Percent This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate may
exceed 80 percent this year due to the worsening economy, local
press reports Wednesday quoted the Institute for Development of
Economics and Finance as saying.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate might even reach three digits, if the
situation did not improve, the institute's program director Nawir
Messi said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Bureau of Statistics, the inflation
rate was 35.05 percent in January-May, compared to 2.71 percent in
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Nawir, one of the factors that would drive
inflation higher this year was the government's moves under
President B. J. Habibie, who replaced Soeharto last month.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Habibie's administration is facing numerous
challenges, mainly in getting the people's support, so he comes up
with populist measures to win the people's hearts."
</P>
<P>
The measures include accommodating demands to raise the
workers' minimum wages and the civil servants' salaries.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to restore ailing banks by injecting
large funds into the banks, some of which should no longer be
saved, was another populist move, he said, adding that the
government had to print more money in order to keep the banks
alive.
</P>
<P>
All these would lead to hyper-inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's banking sector is currently mired in its worst-ever
crisis, with confidence at its lowest ebb. This has forced the
central bank to inject more than 130 trillion rupiah (13 billion
U.S. dollars) in liquidity support into banks whose depositors
have panicked and rushed for their savings.
</P>
<P>
Nawir predicted that the number of poor people would rise to 60
million, much higher than the 50 million estimated by the World
Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
