<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates First Woman to Head FDA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday nominated Jane Henney to become the first female chief of
the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) under the Department of
Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
A cancer specialist at the University of New Mexico, Henney,
51, will succeed former FDA Commissioner David Kessler.
</P>
<P>
A deputy to Kessler from 1992 to 1994, Henney received her
hands-on experience running the agency that regulates 25 percent
of the national economy: drugs, medical devices, foods and
cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
"There is no greater honor than to be asked to return to public
service and to lead the FDA, an agency that plays such a vital
role in protecting and promoting the health of the American
people," Henney said through a spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
The nomination must be confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
A 1973 graduate of Indiana University's medical school, Henney
was a senior investigator at the National Cancer Institute by 1977
and then became its deputy director. In the late 1980s, she ran
the University of Kansas medical school.
</P>
<P>
In New Mexico, Henney supervises a medical school, a college of
pharmacy, and several teaching hospitals. She is also president
of the United States Pharmacopoeia, a nonprofit group that sets
drug purity and quality standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
