<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Basic Education Program in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday approved
a 300 million U.S. dollar loan to Turkey in support of the Basic
Education Program. The program is the Government's action program
to apply its new basic education strategy.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of the strategy and program include to achieve
universal coverage in an expanded, eight-year basic education
cycle, improve the quality and relevance of basic education and
make basic education schools a learning resources for the
community.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project for first-phase implementation of
the program is some 2.52 billion dollars. Since Turkey joined the
World Bank in 1947, Bank commitments to the country have totalled
26.51 billion dollars for 132 projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Institute: World Military Spendings Drop by One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to continued disarmament, the
worldwide military expenditures have dropped by one third to about 680
billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from the high of 1,030 billion dollars in
1987, a German disarmament research institute said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest annual report issued by the Bonn-based
International Center for Conversion (BICC), the world's total military
spendings amounted to about 2.3 percent of the global gross domestic
product (GDP) in 1996, down from five percent in 1987.
</P>
<P>
While disarmament had been registered in most industrialized
countries, a number of Third World countries had increased their
military spendings, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Under the BICC estimates, the total number of soldiers in the world
sank to 22.7 million in 1996 from 23.5 million in 1995 and 28.8
million in 1987.
</P>
<P>
"Despite some setbacks, the worldwide disarmament process has
continued in the second half of the 1990s, but at a relatively slower
pace," the BICC report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiscal Evasion on Rise in Moldova </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Fiscal evasion in 1997 increased
as much as twice in comparison with the precedent year in the
Republic of Moldova, totalling 515 million lei(about 110 million
U.S. dollars), 15 percent of the revenue, the Moldovan BASA-Press
news agency reported on Tuesday quoting a report of the Center for
Strategic Studies and Reforms.
</P>
<P>
The report "showed that taxation "is becoming an activity which
is not based anymore on law and includes some features as the
level of income, profit, added value. It is rather a process of
tax collection based on occasion, on personal relationships".
</P>
<P>
The same document described this "sort of taxation as widely
legalized in Moldova". "If the shadowy economy wins, as it seems
to come true in case of Moldova, it will be hard to believe that
there will be any economic development," the report concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
