<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances Tri-Provincial Highway Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday
approved a 230 million U.S. dollar loan for a Tri-Provincial
Highway Project to further development of highway transport in
the northwestern regions of China.
</P>
<P>
This project will increase the efficiency and safety of
transport in one or two highway priority corridors in the
regions of Inner Mongolia and Ningxia, and the province of
Gansu. New highways will be built and existing highways will be
improved in these corridors in order to facilitate faster social
and economic development in these land-locked provinces.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide improved road access to
targeted poor counties in each of these three provinces. These
provinces have about 7.2 million poor people.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives of the project include promoting the
development of institutional capacities in each of the three
provinces in the areas of highway planning, design, supervision,
training of staff within China and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Cote D'Ivoire's Transport Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday okayed a
180 million U.S. dollar equivalent interest-free credit to finance
a Transport Sector Adjustment/Investment Program in Cote D'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
This project will provide general budgetary support, contribute
to narrowing the external financing gap, and strengthen the
government's ability to ensure availability of routine and
periodic road maintenance funding at sufficient levels and
facilitate transition of several sector organizations from public
to private sector status.
</P>
<P>
The program's main focus is on rehabilitation and maintenance
of existing road infrastructure, on rehabilitating or creating
basic facilities for the provision of efficient road transport
freight and passenger services, selective port investments to
enhance competitiveness and improve environmental protection in
the port zones.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's credit will be channeled through the
International Development Association (IDA), the Bank's
concessional lending wing for developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
