<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Discovery of VX Shows Importance of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Tuesday that discovery of traces of the deadly VX nerve
gas on warheads in Iraq would justify U.S. position to continue
sanctions on Iraq for the safety of America.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior U.S. official, U.N. weapons inspectors,
in a recent routine search of Iraqi missiles, discovered traces of
the deadly VX nerve gas on warheads.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the discovery during a Rose Garden bill-signing
ceremony, Clinton said: "If this report is true, it will just show
that our insistence over these last many years on the U.N.
inspection system is the right thing to do for the safety of
America and the safety of the rest of the world."
</P>
<P>
"We'll stay with the position we've always had: Let the
inspections go forward and don't lift the sanctions until the
resolutions are complied with," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. senior official said the discovery, to be detailed at
the United Nations, will strengthen the hand of the United States
in maintaining tough economic sanctions on Iraq when the issue is
taken up by the Security Council on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, said in New York: "If this allegation is correct... that
will set back Iraq's efforts to try to lift sanctions. It shows
that they've been concealing, they've been lying, and it calls
into question their commitment to disarmament."
</P>
<P>
At a State Department briefing, spokesman James Rubin said: "It
appears to be another case of UNSCOM (the U.N. Special Commission)
having overcome Iraq's deceit on what it has done and it is
doing."
</P>
<P>
He said it was "another in a long series of examples of Iraq's
determined program of deceit, and it demonstrates how important it
is for sanctions to remain in place until Iraq cooperates with
UNSCOM."
</P>
<P>
In Baghdad, Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said Iraqi
scientists had experimented with VX but were unable to turn it
into a weapon. He said in a letter to the Security Council that
1.7 tons of the agent had been produced but it was not of
weapons grade, according to the Iraqi News Agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rekdal's Penalty Kick Sends Norway into Last 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MARSEILLE, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Kjetil Rekdal converted a
89th-minute penalty kick to send Norway into the second round of the
soccer World Cup finals with a 2-1 win over defending champion Brazil
in group A on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rekdal, who plays for German club Hertha Berlin, shot to the
left-hand side of the goal. Brazilian keeper Tafarel dived in the
right direction but the ball just slided past his hands into the net.
</P>
<P>
This was the second time in one year that the Scandinavian squad
has beaten the world champion following their 4-2 win in Oslo last
May.
</P>
<P>
After the first half in which the Norwegians' watertight defence
successfully contained the Brazilian attacks, Bebeto finally found the
net with a diving header 33 minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
Midfielder Denilson dribbled through the left, was tackled down by
a Norwegian defender but struggled up to pass the ball to center for
Bebeto to head past keeper Frode Grodas.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians never appeared secure even after the goal and their
worries materialized in the 83rd minute when Chelsea striker Tore
Andre Flo equalized for Norway.
</P>
<P>
Flo, 25, slotted the ball home on a pass from Liverpool defender
Stig Bjornebye.
</P>
<P>
Lady luck shone on Norway in the 43rd minute when American referee
Esfandiar Baharmast awarded the penalty after Goncalves made a foul in
the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
A loss did not affect Brazil, who had qualified even before the
game. But Norway's victory meant that Morocco were eliminated despite
their 3-0 victory over Scotland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Report Says Angola's UNITA Misses Deadlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Angola's faction of UNITA,
or National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, has failed
to meet agreed deadlines for normalizing state administration in
four strategic areas in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in his
latest report to the Security Council which was made public on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the June 17 report, the areas that have been under
UNITA control are Andulo, Bailundo, Mungo and N'Harea. UNITA
failed twice to oblige its promise to give them to the central
government when deadlines were set for April 1 and May 31.
</P>
<P>
The report said the last two months were marked by a dangerous
deterioration of security situation in 8 of the 18 Angolan
provinces, with recent incidents resulting in the loss of many
lives and displacement of thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
Many of these anti-government attacks were conducted by armed
elements under UNITA control, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan reiterated his call for UNITA
demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council adopted a resolution on June 12 to
impose sanctions on UNITA on June 25 unless UNITA has fully
complied with its obligations by June 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
