<HEADLINE> Train Crash Kills Two in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 23 (Xinhua) -- A train driver and his
assistant were killed and damage estimated at about 12 million
Rand (2.2 million U.S. Dollars) caused when two fuel trains
collided in South Africa's Northern Province Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two trains crashed at a railway crossing between Nylstroom
and Naboomspruit at about 2 a.m. (0000 GMT) and burst into
flames, South African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
One train was loaded with diesel, petrol and paraffin and on
its way to Zimbabwe when it smashed into a second locomotive
pulling 25 empty petrol trucks on its way to Johannesburg, SAPA
reported Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Three of the six locomotives pulling the two trains were burnt
out in the accident and two trucks were derailed.
</P>
<P>
A driver and his assistant were killed instantly in the blaze.
</P>
<P>
Over 120 meters of overhead power lines and 40 meters of track
were damaged.
</P>
<P>
The north-bound line through Northern Province and countries
beyond South Africa's northern borders was closed for the rest of
the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
