<HEADLINE> Luzkov: Russia Opposes Military Intervention on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Mayor of Moscow Yuri
Luzkov said here Tuesday that Russia opposed the use of force to
resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos, Luzkov said Russia was against military intervention,
use of force and unilateral actions from any military alliance,
including the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that Russia was deeply concerned about the
developments in the Balkans, particularly in the Yugoslav province
of Kosovo where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of its nearly
2 million population.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the outcome of these situations were deaths
and the violation of rights, such as sovereign right.
</P>
<P>
If the international community was to be taking decisions
concerning the fate of countries, then these decisions must be
taken in conditions of peace and in a spirit of negotiations, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been running high in Kosovo since February when
Serbian police clashed with ethnic Albanians seeking independence
from Belgrade and integration into neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
Western countries have warned that they have almost run out of
options to end the crisis except military intervention. 
</P>
