<HEADLINE> No Obstacles in Face of Arab Summit: Egyptian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Tuesday In Riyadh, Saudi Arabia that there are no
obstacles in face of holding an Arab summit, but the success of
such a meeting requires adequate preparations.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in the Saudi capital, Moussa told reporters
that "there are calls for a well-prepared Arab summit, that does
not mean the postponing or delaying the convocation of such a
summit."
</P>
<P>
"This means that the Arab world is thinking wisely and is
serious to take a unified stand in face of the current situation
in the peace process," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz said Monday during a weekly
cabinet session that any Arab summit held without good
preparation would be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about the Arab stand regarding the
expansion of Jerusalem, Moussa said "the decision by Israel to
expand Jerusalem is a violation to international resolutions which
forbid any geographical changes or restructuring the city legally
or administratively."
</P>
<P>
Moussa is in Saudi Arabia to chair with his Saudi counterpart
Prince Saud Al-Faisal a session of the Joint Egyptian-Saudi
Higher Committee.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian ambassador to Saudi Arabia Helmi Bdeir said the
committee is due to discuss ways of promotion of bilateral ties
and latest developments in the Arab and Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Bdeir was quoted by the Kuwaiti News Agency as saying that the
discussion will also touch issues on the stalled Middle East
peace process and current efforts to hold an Arab summit to
counter Israel's anti-peace policy.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Gulf region and the development of
relations with Iran will also be tackled by both foreign
ministers, Bdeir said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said a preparatory meeting was held to
finalize the agenda for the session of the Joint Higher
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Abu Zaid, Moussa's aid who co-chaired the two-day meeting,
said they discussed economic, trade and investment cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
