<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Veto Iran Sanctions Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has decided to veto legislation on Iranian sanctions as its
regimes "produce hopeless shackles on the presidency to handle
U.S. foreign policy, the White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
President's Press Secretary Mike McCurry told reporters he
expected the president would return the Iran Missile
Proliferation Act to Congress later on Tuesday, and the White
House would then issue a veto statement on that.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, passed by Congress, would automatically
impose sanctions on any foreign government or business that
supplies ballistic missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Congress gave little flexibility in the act to
the president when he is pursuing a new relationship with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Essentially, there is no flexibility in the act passed by
Congress that allows the president to work through problems," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's decision to veto the legislation came less than a
week after he expressed hope for "a genuine reconciliation with
Iran" if it complies with so-called standards the United States
has set as conditions for normalization of their relations,
which include suspension of support of terrorism, of
distribution of weapons of mass destruction and of opposition of
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has already eased travel to the
United States for Iranians and is supporting cultural and
academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton believed Congress is trying to put
"hopeless shackles on the presidency with the legislation and to
"micromanage" U.S. foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He said Clinton also considered the threshold for issuing
sanctions too low.
</P>
<P>
"The threshold set for imposition of sanctions is so low that
you could conceivably have situations in the future in which the
United States government might improperly or incorrectly impose
sanctions, which would cast out on the credibility of all the
sanctions regimes that we maintain," he said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton would continue to work with Russia on
U.S. concern about the proliferation of missile technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980624.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nominee Calls for Reducing Political Battling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The nominee to be director of
the Census Bureau of the United States said he wants the political
battling reduced over the national head count in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Given the high stakes, it is unfortunate that Census 2000 has
become prey to partisan disagreements. These differences place
Census 2000 at risk by delaying the bureau's preparation in the
enormously complex task of accurately counting the American
people," Kenneth Prewitt said at a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Secretary William M. Daley made the nomination at the
news conference.
</P>
<P>
Prewitt, head of the Social Science Research Council in New
York, would succeed Martha Farnsworth Riche, who left the Census
post in January.
</P>
<P>
The nomination needs to be confirmed by the Senate and could
become controversial because of the dispute over whether the
Census, scheduled for April 1, 2000, should include a statistical
method known as sampling, which is strongly opposed by Republicans
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
The use of statistical sampling in census has become a highly
controversial issue in the planning for the 2000 count with the
sides divided largely along party lines.
</P>
<P>
Democrats favor the plan, contending that it will reduce the
undercount that missed some four million people in 1990.
</P>
<P>
But Republicans counter that it opens the way for increasing
the count of minorities, who generally vote for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Prewitt said his job will be to ensure the Census is as
accurate as possible within any limits set by Congress, the courts
or the administration.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that sampling, properly used and employed,
can improve the accuracy of the count," he said. But "there are
very complicated issues about the sampling designs and uncertainty
about whether it will be allowed."
</P>
<P>
Confirmation will be done by the Senate, but it generally
listens closely to the opinions of House members, who are most
directly affected by the national head count. Census results are
used to reapportion seats in the House as well as in the
distribution of federal funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
