<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Relations with Colombia Open New Page </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it is ready to assist the Colombian government in its
efforts to search for peace and the relations between the two
nations can open a new page.
</P>
<P>
Andres Pastrana, Colombia's president-elect, said that he would
like to see the United States playing a major role in fight
against drug trafficking and the negotiations with the left-wing
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that President-elect Pastrana expressed interest
in U.S. involvement in the Colombian peace process during a press
conference yesterday," said State Department spokesman James
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to assist the government of Colombia in its
efforts to search for peace. We are prepared to discuss this and
other issues with President-elect Pastrana in the coming days,"
Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration "stand ready to assist in encouraging
and supporting a peace process in Colombia," noted the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "Obviously, it is up to the government of
Colombia to determine what role it foresees for other countries in
these negotiations."
</P>
<P>
On the fight against drugs, Rubin said the U.S. does want to
cooperate more closely with the government of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
"When we get to a point where we have greater contact with the
new leadership, then we will be in a position to discuss details,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we are hopeful that we can turn over a new page in
U.S.-Colombian relations and vastly improve, not only the fight
against narcotics traffickers but also the whole array of
U.S.-Colombian bilateral issues," said Rubin.  
</P>
